WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.900
[Amit Varma]: Mary Oliver is one of my favourite poets and one of my favourite lines by her goes thus

00:00:09.900 --> 00:00:16.340
[Amit Varma]: quote, everything that was broken has forgotten its brokenness, stop quote. I look around

00:00:16.340 --> 00:00:20.980
[Amit Varma]: and I see much that is breaking and is fresh in our minds but will seem normal tomorrow

00:00:20.980 --> 00:00:25.220
[Amit Varma]: and I also see so much that has been wrong for 75 years and we don't even think of

00:00:25.220 --> 00:00:29.420
[Amit Varma]: it as a problem because it's part of the fabric of our lives. If we are lucky enough

00:00:29.420 --> 00:00:34.380
[Amit Varma]: to be well off, the world outside our bubble is unseen to us. There is so much shit going

00:00:34.380 --> 00:00:38.180
[Amit Varma]: on around us that we have normalised. There is no rule of law in this country for most

00:00:38.180 --> 00:00:42.820
[Amit Varma]: people, women are second class citizens, our education system is broken, healthcare is

00:00:42.820 --> 00:00:48.340
[Amit Varma]: broken, the legal system is broken, we still have the wild caste system with us, 3000 children

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:53.020
[Amit Varma]: still die of starvation every day, a quarter of our kids are still malnourished and at

00:00:53.020 --> 00:00:58.180
[Amit Varma]: this moment in time, our society is being torn apart by anti-Muslim bigots who are destroying

00:00:58.180 --> 00:01:03.020
[Amit Varma]: all that is best about India. And even if we sometimes do protest some of this, we get

00:01:03.020 --> 00:01:08.540
[Amit Varma]: tired, we get back to our lives, the old abnormal becomes a new normal. It is what it is. That

00:01:08.540 --> 00:01:13.300
[Amit Varma]: is why, on this show at least, I try to keep outraging, keep dissenting, maybe against

00:01:13.300 --> 00:01:18.580
[Amit Varma]: a regime, maybe against a conventional way of thinking, maybe just against bad economics

00:01:18.580 --> 00:01:23.220
[Amit Varma]: which is almost written into India's DNA. A couple of times a year, I get economists

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:27.580
[Amit Varma]: together and do an episode to take stock of the economy. Our problems are chronic, so

00:01:27.580 --> 00:01:32.140
[Amit Varma]: it might seem like we keep saying the same things, repackaging the same old laments,

00:01:32.140 --> 00:01:36.140
[Amit Varma]: but I believe it is important to do so. We cannot take the injustice of this world for

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:41.260
[Amit Varma]: granted. And a lot of this injustice has to do with economics. Bad economics kept hundreds

00:01:41.260 --> 00:01:46.420
[Amit Varma]: of millions of people in India in poverty for decades longer than necessary. Bad economics

00:01:46.420 --> 00:01:51.660
[Amit Varma]: is responsible for people slipping back into poverty today. Bad economics has humanitarian

00:01:51.660 --> 00:02:11.140
[Unknown]: consequences and that's why we should never shut up about it.

00:02:11.140 --> 00:02:14.820
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and The Unseen. My guests today are the economists Rajeshwari Sengupta

00:02:14.820 --> 00:02:19.620
[Amit Varma]: and Shreyana Bhattacharya, both of whom have been my guests before and have recorded memorable

00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:24.980
[Amit Varma]: episodes with me. I recorded an episode on the GDP with Rajeshwari, how GDP is flawed

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:30.500
[Amit Varma]: in concept and messed up in practice, especially in India. Besides that powerful primer, we

00:02:30.500 --> 00:02:34.740
[Amit Varma]: also did an episode where she and I and two other guests laid out our dream reforms for

00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:40.420
[Amit Varma]: India. And Shreyana appeared on an episode from earlier this year called The Loneliness

00:02:40.420 --> 00:02:44.780
[Amit Varma]: of the Indian Woman, which has since become one of the most popular episodes of the show

00:02:44.780 --> 00:02:48.500
[Amit Varma]: and has struck a chord with so many people everywhere. If you haven't already heard

00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:54.060
[Amit Varma]: it, I recommend you listen. So many TIL moments. Now, when I heard Shreyana was coming to Bombay,

00:02:54.060 --> 00:02:58.380
[Amit Varma]: I thought it was a perfect chance to do a state of the economy kind of episode with

00:02:58.380 --> 00:03:03.100
[Amit Varma]: her and Rajeshwari. Once they both agreed, I realised that we now had the most Bengalis

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:07.580
[Amit Varma]: that had ever been inside my home studio. They're both bong, I'm half bong, so that's

00:03:07.580 --> 00:03:11.820
[Amit Varma]: two and a half bongs, which is appropriate for this episode because I wanted it to be

00:03:11.820 --> 00:03:18.300
[Amit Varma]: like an adda. No structure, just chill together, ramble, talk about this and that, let it flow.

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:22.780
[Amit Varma]: We ended up speaking about economics, society, the imposter syndrome, how women manage in

00:03:22.780 --> 00:03:27.500
[Amit Varma]: a male-dominated profession, how inflation affects women in a greater way than men, the

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:32.780
[Amit Varma]: problems with academia and Delhi high society, and so on. We answered a few questions that

00:03:32.780 --> 00:03:37.020
[Amit Varma]: had been posed to us on Twitter. And at one point, we were disturbed by the loud sound

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:41.900
[Amit Varma]: of a drill from somewhere, which my brilliant editor Gaurav Chintamani managed to hide completely,

00:03:41.900 --> 00:03:46.500
[Amit Varma]: but it still rattled us and I had to stop and figure out which flat it was coming from

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:50.940
[Amit Varma]: and get them to chill, and so on and so forth. You'll hear about that also in the episode.

00:03:50.940 --> 00:03:55.140
[Amit Varma]: So well, I mean, enjoy the conversation. But before that, let's take a quick commercial

00:03:55.140 --> 00:03:56.140
