[Guest 2]: Yes. No pressure again.

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:10.140
[Amit Varma]: Great. So I kind of want to start with you, Rajeshwari, because, you know, these days

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:15.100
[Amit Varma]: the episode has evolved into this form where I spend a lot of time talking to people about,

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:18.420
[Amit Varma]: you know, their childhood, where they came from, the backgrounds, almost like a little

00:06:18.420 --> 00:06:23.060
[Amit Varma]: oral history, as someone called it. And while you and I have done a couple of episodes before,

00:06:23.060 --> 00:06:28.620
[Amit Varma]: we haven't done that part of it. And I'm thinking, OK, I know how she thinks, but I don't know

00:06:28.620 --> 00:06:29.620
[Amit Varma]: me.

00:06:29.620 --> 00:06:33.220
[Amit Varma]: But I don't know you. And I'd like you to start by telling me about your recent holiday,

00:06:33.220 --> 00:06:37.660
[Amit Varma]: because just before this recording, you were telling me about this post-apocalyptic landscape

00:06:37.660 --> 00:06:41.460
[Amit Varma]: you went to, where you were in the middle of the sea and there was no water, which is

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:44.300
[Amit Varma]: so fascinating. So tell me about that.

00:06:44.300 --> 00:06:49.060
[Guest 1]: So thanks, Amit. And let me just start by saying I have no idea why people would be

00:06:49.060 --> 00:06:55.500
[Guest 1]: interested at all in my life story. But since I'm here in the chair, I'll get talking. So

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:59.020
[Guest 1]: over the long weekend, we just decided to and we have been doing a lot of road trips

00:06:59.020 --> 00:07:02.860
[Guest 1]: during the lockdown since we couldn't go anywhere else. And this is the first time we started

00:07:02.860 --> 00:07:06.820
[Guest 1]: exploring Maharashtra, despite having lived in Bombay for the last seven years. So we

00:07:06.820 --> 00:07:10.620
[Guest 1]: decided that we've been almost everywhere that people usually go to. And there's one

00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:15.160
[Guest 1]: place that is left that we have been hearing a lot about, and that's Bordi and Dahanu.

00:07:15.160 --> 00:07:19.820
[Guest 1]: So we decided to go there, a bunch of three families with all our kids and everything.

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:23.380
[Guest 1]: And little did we realize, of course, that Bordi and Dahanu are closer to the Gujarat

00:07:23.380 --> 00:07:30.160
[Guest 1]: border, which means it's incredibly hot. But still, we went. And so one of the main attractions

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:35.020
[Guest 1]: of Bordi is the beach. So we go to the beach the evening of the day when we reach the place

00:07:35.020 --> 00:07:40.700
[Guest 1]: and we find that there's a low tide. Now, what we know of low tide from places like

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:44.740
[Guest 1]: Juhu Beach, etc. is that the water recedes a little bit and then after a point it comes

00:07:44.740 --> 00:07:49.540
[Guest 1]: back, right? Whereas on Bordi Beach, we discovered that the sea has literally retreated more

00:07:49.540 --> 00:07:55.180
[Guest 1]: than 12 to 15 kilometers, if not more. So you can't see the water at all standing on

00:07:55.180 --> 00:08:01.260
[Guest 1]: the beach. And what you see is kilometer and kilometer of what looks like mirage, right?

00:08:01.260 --> 00:08:04.900
[Guest 1]: Because there's a shimmery because of the sun, the setting sun, the little bit of shimmering

00:08:04.900 --> 00:08:09.460
[Guest 1]: on the surface, because it's all watery mud, because the sea has retreated. And it's all

00:08:09.460 --> 00:08:15.580
[Guest 1]: slush and black earth kind of thing. And you can keep walking for about 10-12 kilometers

00:08:15.580 --> 00:08:20.820
[Guest 1]: on the seabed, yet not reach the sea. And there was nobody else around, it was just

00:08:20.820 --> 00:08:26.780
[Guest 1]: us. So exactly as I said, it really felt apocalyptic, because in the sense that you feel that it's

00:08:26.780 --> 00:08:31.380
[Guest 1]: the end of the world, and the sea has retreated somewhere far away, and you can't reach it.

00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:35.620
[Guest 1]: And at least for me, I felt this irresistible pull that I have to keep walking towards the

00:08:35.620 --> 00:08:41.020
[Guest 1]: sea to find how far the water is. So we kept walking and after a point of time, I think

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:46.780
[Guest 1]: we walked quite a bit. And it was just us in the middle of this vast seabed with no

00:08:46.780 --> 00:08:51.020
[Guest 1]: water anywhere. And the actual beach is far away, the water is somewhere else, and we

00:08:51.020 --> 00:08:56.620
[Guest 1]: were in the middle of nowhere literally. So it was a surreal feeling. And that ended up

00:08:56.620 --> 00:09:01.740
[Guest 1]: being my definition of having fun in Bodhi. But it was fascinating. I have not seen something

00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:06.540
[Guest 1]: like this ever before. And then we went back the next day to see the sea has to come back

00:09:06.540 --> 00:09:11.260
[Guest 1]: at some point of time. And it did, the high tide was spectacular as well. So that was

00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:12.780
[Guest 1]: my long weekend, basically.

00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:17.580
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's damn scary, because, you know, what one hears of the tsunami, since the tsunami

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:22.380
[Amit Varma]: struck in 2003, is that the sea recedes a lot, and then it comes back. So if I saw the

00:09:22.380 --> 00:09:26.060
[Amit Varma]: sea had gone this far back, I would be too scared. I'd probably go further inland rather

00:09:26.060 --> 00:09:27.660
[Guest 1]: than towards the sea.

00:09:27.660 --> 00:09:30.940
[Guest 1]: In fact, we had to take a call when the sun was setting. And we knew that the time of

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:34.580
[Guest 1]: the high tide was approaching. And we had gone really far into the seabed that we had

00:09:34.580 --> 00:09:38.620
[Guest 1]: to start walking back. And it's pitch dark. I mean, once you get pitch dark, there's no,

00:09:38.620 --> 00:09:42.940
[Guest 1]: there's nothing whatsoever. So we had to take a call that do we keep going towards in search

00:09:42.940 --> 00:09:47.300
[Guest 1]: of the water? Do we just walk back? So we all decided to walk back all the for a split

00:09:47.300 --> 00:09:49.100
[Guest 1]: second I was in two minds.

00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:50.100
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

00:09:50.100 --> 00:09:51.620
[Amit Varma]: It was irresistible.

00:09:51.620 --> 00:09:54.540
[Amit Varma]: So have any of you guys seen Krzysztof Kieslowski's films?

00:09:54.540 --> 00:09:55.540
[Amit Varma]: No.

00:09:55.540 --> 00:09:59.700
[Amit Varma]: I call it you know, the first great web series in a sense. He made a series of 10 films for

00:09:59.700 --> 00:10:05.020
[Amit Varma]: Polish television in 91 or 90 or something like that called Decalogue, with each film

00:10:05.020 --> 00:10:10.940
[Amit Varma]: being on one of the 10 commandments. And the first of those was called Thou shalt have

00:10:10.940 --> 00:10:14.740
[Amit Varma]: no other God than me. It was based on that commandment. And obviously, I don't even think

00:10:14.740 --> 00:10:18.980
[Amit Varma]: he's necessarily a believer, but it was just interesting reinterpretations. And it's about

00:10:18.980 --> 00:10:23.940
[Amit Varma]: a guy whose, you know, son wants to go skating in a lake that has just gotten frozen up and

00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:28.400
[Amit Varma]: he's complete scientific temperament and he does a math and everything. So he figures

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:33.020
[Amit Varma]: out exactly that it is not safe today, it is not safe tomorrow, it is safe on Wednesday,

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:35.940
[Amit Varma]: because that's where the temperature will be and you can go skating and nothing will

00:10:35.940 --> 00:10:39.260
[Amit Varma]: happen and all of that. And not to give it, I mean, the spoiler doesn't matter because

00:10:39.260 --> 00:10:43.140
[Amit Varma]: it's just such a great film and I watch it again and again. His son goes out and drowns,

00:10:43.140 --> 00:10:47.580
[Amit Varma]: the ice breaks. And then the last shot of that little short film is that while he's

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:51.420
[Amit Varma]: at the edge of the water, and he's thinking about his son, in the distance, he sees as

00:10:51.420 --> 00:10:54.980
[Amit Varma]: a homeless tramp who's lit a fire by the side of the lake.

00:10:54.980 --> 00:10:55.980
[Amit Varma]: Ouch.

00:10:55.980 --> 00:11:00.020
[Amit Varma]: You know, so if you get the connection with Thou shalt have no other God but me, just

00:11:00.020 --> 00:11:03.420
[Amit Varma]: tremendous. And when you were speaking of doing calculations of what time the high tide

00:11:03.420 --> 00:11:06.380
[Guest 1]: will come in, I was like, you fool, come back.

00:11:06.380 --> 00:11:07.380
[Guest 1]: Come back.

00:11:07.380 --> 00:11:08.380
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:11:08.380 --> 00:11:12.900
[Guest 1]: Yeah. So my daughter, she's four years old. She was obviously scared because I mean, it

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:17.180
[Guest 1]: was surreal to me for her, she had never seen something like that. So she decided to stay

00:11:17.180 --> 00:11:19.940
[Guest 1]: back on the beach and my husband was torn in between. Should I go with the wife? Should

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:23.900
[Guest 1]: I go with the daughter? So I think he also went more towards the beach. But then for

00:11:23.900 --> 00:11:28.060
[Guest 1]: me, it was just, I mean, you know, you just felt, you just feel like you keep walking

00:11:28.060 --> 00:11:32.460
[Guest 1]: and whatever happens happens. I mean, at some point you just hit the sea, nothing more happens.

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:35.900
[Guest 1]: But it's just that the time, it's just so far away, you keep walking and then it can

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:40.260
[Guest 1]: get dark, the high tide can come, you may not have enough time to walk back, all of

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:43.140
[Guest 1]: those things. So it was spooky, but it was fascinating.

00:11:43.140 --> 00:11:47.260
[Guest 1]: Fabulous. And people say economists are boring people. What rubbish, what do you mean they

00:11:47.260 --> 00:11:48.260
[Guest 1]: are?

00:11:48.260 --> 00:11:51.260
[Guest 1]: Who are these people who say economists are boring people?

00:11:51.260 --> 00:11:52.260
[Unknown]: Economists.

00:11:52.260 --> 00:11:56.100
[Guest 1]: I'm definitely not one of them.

00:11:56.100 --> 00:11:59.620
[Amit Varma]: What's the most adventurous thing you've done, Shreyana? Have you been reckless?

00:11:59.620 --> 00:12:05.300
[Guest 2]: No, I have never been reckless. I think I've just written my recklessness away. And now

00:12:05.300 --> 00:12:10.700
[Guest 2]: I'm leading the life of a very boring urban hermit in Delhi. I actually, you know, actually

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:16.060
[Guest 2]: listening to you, I'm realizing I haven't done any travel recently. I've just been broadly

00:12:16.060 --> 00:12:19.700
[Guest 2]: in Delhi. And now with the book, a little bit of travel has now started to happen, which

00:12:19.700 --> 00:12:26.140
[Guest 2]: is exciting. But I'm really looking forward to a holiday, which would be nice. But going

00:12:26.140 --> 00:12:32.220
[Guest 2]: back to this thing about economists being boring, I mean, have you seen the current

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:36.460
[Guest 2]: conversations between all of us? It's like we're saying the same thing to each other

00:12:36.460 --> 00:12:40.460
[Guest 2]: constantly and it's getting quite repetitive and boring. So it's nice that you're discussing

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:46.460
[Guest 2]: holidays now, because I do think that there is just general fatigue in the discourse.

00:12:46.460 --> 00:12:51.700
[Guest 1]: I think that given that we are living in India, it's always very adventurous and exciting

00:12:51.700 --> 00:12:55.300
[Guest 1]: to be an economist in India, because there is always something or the other that's happening.

00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:59.900
[Guest 1]: I mean, being an economist in the US is damn boring, because nothing much happens there.

00:12:59.900 --> 00:13:04.300
[Guest 1]: Being an economist in India, but one day you have a demonetization. One day you have a

00:13:04.300 --> 00:13:08.740
[Guest 1]: you know, a lockdown that is announced with a four hours notice to the utmost misery of

00:13:08.740 --> 00:13:13.260
[Guest 1]: most people. And then one day you have like a GST, which is implemented with the shoddiest

00:13:13.260 --> 00:13:17.260
[Guest 1]: possible manner. There's always something or the other happening. And I just feel that

00:13:17.260 --> 00:13:21.940
[Guest 1]: it's difficult to almost keep pace with how things are changing. And it's like last year,

00:13:21.940 --> 00:13:25.980
[Guest 1]: we were thinking of the pandemic and the pandemic is receding, and the economy is going to come

00:13:25.980 --> 00:13:31.460
[Guest 1]: out of it. And then bang, you get hit by geopolitical Russia-Ukraine war, then bang, you have US

00:13:31.460 --> 00:13:34.980
[Guest 1]: inflation higher than in the last 40 years. There's constantly something or the other

00:13:34.980 --> 00:13:39.380
[Guest 1]: happening. So I think there is, I mean, I don't get bored with the discourse, I think

00:13:39.380 --> 00:13:44.980
[Guest 1]: primarily because in India, there is just so many shocks and so many policies gone wrong.

00:13:44.980 --> 00:13:49.620
[Guest 2]: But I think that's the source of my boredom, which is that I think we keep saying things,

00:13:49.620 --> 00:13:53.180
[Guest 2]: and then things just go wrong. And I feel like now we're just stuck in this cycle of

00:13:53.180 --> 00:13:57.300
[Guest 2]: just anticipating the next thing that will potentially happen. And then a bunch of us

00:13:57.300 --> 00:14:01.980
[Guest 2]: will write things and a bunch of us will say a lot. And then we have a set of institutions

00:14:01.980 --> 00:14:07.500
[Guest 2]: and you're giggling now, I can see you, you know, who will ignore everything that useful

00:14:07.500 --> 00:14:15.500
[Guest 2]: that has to be said. So you know what I mean? My boredom is not with the state of the fact

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:18.500
[Guest 2]: that we have analysis to do, although there's no data. And I know we'll come to that. I

00:14:18.500 --> 00:14:24.020
[Guest 2]: hope we'll come to that. I really do want to come to that. But even if there were data

00:14:24.020 --> 00:14:30.180
[Guest 2]: and we're using data, I think where my sense of the cyclical fatigue has come in is just

00:14:30.180 --> 00:14:35.900
[Guest 2]: the fact that we say stuff, and then we all get very excited about it. But I just, you

00:14:35.900 --> 00:14:42.980
[Guest 2]: know, it's, it's this, it's quite, I have to say, it's actually quite dispiriting. I

00:14:42.980 --> 00:14:47.580
[Guest 2]: mean, at this stage, I sort of I feel that way. I'm curious what you think.

00:14:47.580 --> 00:14:52.340
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I don't feel dispirited. At the same time, I wouldn't say that I feel extremely

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:57.900
[Guest 1]: optimistic either. Right. But I find a lot of I take a lot of confidence from the fact

00:14:57.900 --> 00:15:02.460
[Guest 1]: that economists still have a lot of energy to keep doing what we are doing, despite the

00:15:02.460 --> 00:15:06.060
[Guest 1]: fact that yes, I mean, things have happened. And whatever we are saying, whatever we are

00:15:06.060 --> 00:15:10.500
[Guest 1]: prescribing and not being implemented. But at the same time, if you take a very long

00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:15.900
[Guest 1]: arc of modern history, like even just like, even for India, like the last 30, 40 years,

00:15:15.900 --> 00:15:20.220
[Guest 1]: no, even for 30, 40 years in India, right? I mean, where we were 40 years back, and where

00:15:20.220 --> 00:15:24.380
[Guest 1]: we are today, definitely, there has been a significant amount of change and improvement.

00:15:24.380 --> 00:15:28.740
[Guest 1]: And the way economists have analysed things, the way we have come up with policy prescriptions,

00:15:28.740 --> 00:15:32.620
[Guest 1]: some of which has helped, some of which has itself changed. So I don't think yes, if you

00:15:32.620 --> 00:15:37.260
[Guest 1]: take an immediate, short term view that okay, but crisis keeps happening, and we keep saying

00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:40.460
[Unknown]: this is a mistake, and that is a mistake, and nobody's listening to us, right? But at

00:15:40.460 --> 00:15:44.380
[Guest 1]: the same time, if you look at again, as I said, 30, 40 years, people have listened and

00:15:44.380 --> 00:15:45.380
[Guest 1]: things have changed.

00:15:45.380 --> 00:15:49.140
[Guest 2]: I don't know whether we have another 30, 40 years looking at the state of the economy

00:15:49.140 --> 00:15:53.380
[Guest 2]: is right now, where we don't know there's a lot of debate about what's happening to

00:15:53.380 --> 00:15:59.900
[Guest 2]: precarity in the job market, although I wonder about that. But I really wonder, I mean, I

00:15:59.900 --> 00:16:06.340
[Guest 2]: think we need some very serious investments and decisions right now, in fact, given the

00:16:06.340 --> 00:16:07.340
[Guest 1]: coming out ofâ€¦

00:16:07.340 --> 00:16:11.460
[Guest 1]: What has happened is, I mean, the reason why the despondency becomes bigger now is in the

00:16:11.460 --> 00:16:17.300
[Guest 1]: current dispensation, at least. There has been an effort to keep, I mean, if I may call

00:16:17.300 --> 00:16:21.260
[Guest 1]: them experts, or whatever you want to call them, right? There has been a conscious effort

00:16:21.260 --> 00:16:26.420
[Guest 1]: to keep them at bay, to keep them away, and to not involve them in any kind of decision

00:16:26.420 --> 00:16:31.420
[Guest 1]: making, any kind of policy analysis. And we have seen an exodus of people from India,

00:16:31.420 --> 00:16:36.140
[Guest 1]: we have seen all the other economists have just withdrawn in their own echo chambers,

00:16:36.140 --> 00:16:39.660
[Guest 1]: and we are just talking to each other, because nobody's interested to talk to us. And that

00:16:39.660 --> 00:16:43.740
[Guest 1]: is something that I think the authorities and the policymakers have done, and they have

00:16:43.740 --> 00:16:47.180
[Guest 1]: taken this decision that we don't want to engage with them anymore. But I also think

00:16:47.180 --> 00:16:51.300
[Guest 1]: that this is a wave. I mean, again, I have a very long term view of things. And I think

00:16:51.300 --> 00:16:54.980
[Guest 1]: it is a wave, and over a period of time, when they do realize that things are getting really,

00:16:54.980 --> 00:16:58.780
[Guest 1]: really bad, and it's already happening. At some point, you have to start engaging with

00:16:58.780 --> 00:17:02.780
[Guest 1]: experts, you have to start engaging with the economists and understand what exactly what

00:17:02.780 --> 00:17:06.820
[Guest 1]: are the ideas they're talking about. I mean, 1991 reforms happened. And imagine the way

00:17:06.820 --> 00:17:12.020
[Guest 1]: they happened till 1991, nobody was really paying attention to that side of economics,

00:17:12.020 --> 00:17:16.740
[Guest 1]: so to speak, and then boom, it happened. And they had every incentive to roll back the

00:17:16.740 --> 00:17:21.380
[Guest 1]: reforms once the crisis was averted, and they did not. They stuck to the reforms, and they

00:17:21.380 --> 00:17:25.580
[Guest 1]: sustained the energy and the momentum of the reforms. And I think economists played a fairly

00:17:25.580 --> 00:17:30.660
[Guest 1]: important role then. And since then, I think from 2010 onwards, particularly, there has

00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:36.740
[Guest 1]: been a, you know, sort of slow withdrawal from expertise, from specialization, from

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:41.740
[Guest 1]: any kind of intellectual discourse. And I'm hoping at least that that's another wave and

00:17:41.740 --> 00:17:44.860
[Guest 1]: soon they will have to realize that this is not working out.

00:17:44.860 --> 00:17:49.500
[Guest 2]: I mean, if I look at just what's happening now, my sense almost is that there's almost

00:17:49.500 --> 00:17:57.380
[Guest 2]: a lot of regurgitating of the common sense analytics and ideas and tropes of economics,

00:17:57.380 --> 00:18:05.260
[Guest 2]: even amongst actually our politics or policymakers. But the impetus to take decisions, I mean,

00:18:05.260 --> 00:18:10.540
[Guest 2]: I think the 1990s, in fact, that reform stories, you know, Amit's done so many shows on this.

00:18:10.540 --> 00:18:14.940
[Guest 2]: It's a very powerful example of, well, we knew the ideas, but then it took sort of a

00:18:14.940 --> 00:18:19.580
[Guest 2]: whole set. It's an apparatus, right, that has to act and then has to implement and roll

00:18:19.580 --> 00:18:24.620
[Guest 2]: out and check whether the rollout is working in a certain direction. I'm not sure, I think

00:18:24.620 --> 00:18:29.940
[Guest 2]: looking at the current state of affairs, where that apparatus right now lies. So I don't

00:18:29.940 --> 00:18:36.460
[Guest 2]: think, and to me, remember, I mean, it's not just about economics in academic economics.

00:18:36.460 --> 00:18:40.620
[Guest 2]: I'm thinking of the Indian Economic Service. I'm thinking of economists within the apparatus

00:18:40.620 --> 00:18:47.620
[Guest 2]: who are supposed to form this crux of a core constituency that will fight for reform within.

00:18:47.620 --> 00:18:52.980
[Guest 2]: And I think that's where I see a lot more despondency, just informally, what one sees

00:18:52.980 --> 00:18:59.500
[Guest 2]: when one is interacting with government agencies, and just the general discourse. And so what

00:18:59.500 --> 00:19:04.740
[Guest 2]: worries me sometimes is I almost feel that there's now currently like an incentive to

00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:09.980
[Guest 2]: live in even deeper bubbles, more energetic and energized bubbles, because it's wonderful

00:19:09.980 --> 00:19:16.580
[Guest 2]: then to be in that bubble and find like minded people who you can talk to. But I think beyond

00:19:16.580 --> 00:19:20.740
[Guest 2]: those individual, I wouldn't even call them echo chambers, because I think that's doing

00:19:20.740 --> 00:19:25.660
[Guest 2]: a disservice. I think they are bubbles of thoughts and very important thoughts. But

00:19:25.660 --> 00:19:29.140
[Guest 2]: I just don't know beyond that. I mean, you remember, there was that fabulous book that

00:19:29.140 --> 00:19:34.820
[Guest 2]: came out, I'm going to say before the pandemic, it had essays by people like Pranjul Bhandari

00:19:34.820 --> 00:19:38.300
[Guest 2]: and Raghuram Rajan and Abhijit, on sort of all kinds of things that you could do with

00:19:38.300 --> 00:19:43.540
[Guest 2]: the economy, really useful suggestions, and very concrete, actually, it was a very refreshing

00:19:43.540 --> 00:19:48.140
[Guest 2]: book, because they really made it. I actually now almost wondered, you know, if you just

00:19:48.140 --> 00:19:53.500
[Guest 2]: go back to those texts and just see, well, how much of what was low hanging fruit has

00:19:53.500 --> 00:19:58.220
[Guest 2]: happened or not happened, I think we'll find very dismal results. And I don't think the

00:19:58.220 --> 00:20:03.900
[Guest 2]: reason is academic economists are not energized and enthusiastic. I think there's a whole

00:20:03.900 --> 00:20:09.780
[Guest 2]: community that's doing economics and the job of economic policymaking and decision making,

00:20:09.780 --> 00:20:13.900
[Guest 2]: which lies within government, lies within local think tanks, support groups, lobbies,

00:20:13.900 --> 00:20:19.060
[Guest 2]: I think it's a very complex set of actors. And there, I almost sense that there's a lot

00:20:19.060 --> 00:20:24.940
[Guest 2]: of parroting of the words and the tropes. But the conviction perhaps, maybe conviction

00:20:24.940 --> 00:20:30.620
[Guest 2]: is a very strong word, but the zeal to sort of say, we need to do this. I don't know where

00:20:30.620 --> 00:20:32.620
[Guest 1]: that's evaporating. It's very sad.

00:20:32.620 --> 00:20:37.340
[Guest 1]: There is also the element that, at least again, in the last few years, the way things have

00:20:37.340 --> 00:20:43.260
[Guest 1]: evolved is that if you, let's say, believe in something, an economic policy or an economic

00:20:43.260 --> 00:20:48.540
[Guest 1]: recommendation, it need not, just on the merit of the economic argument, it may not be accepted

00:20:48.540 --> 00:20:53.740
[Guest 1]: as long as it doesn't echo with the sort of what I call the quote unquote party line,

00:20:53.740 --> 00:20:58.580
[Guest 1]: right? I mean, unless you are really talking in terms of what they want to hear, unless

00:20:58.580 --> 00:21:02.580
[Guest 1]: you are really saying, you're sort of playing to the gallery, even if there is an economic

00:21:02.580 --> 00:21:06.220
[Guest 1]: merit to the argument, they don't want to hear it. And they're going to choose the arguments

00:21:06.220 --> 00:21:10.420
[Guest 1]: of the people who are talking about stuff that they want to hear. Now, be that as it

00:21:10.420 --> 00:21:14.740
[Guest 1]: may, I think at the same time, it is very important to keep talking about the ideas

00:21:14.740 --> 00:21:19.300
[Guest 1]: and keep discussing and debating everything that we are doing. Because, as I said, at

00:21:19.300 --> 00:21:23.940
[Guest 1]: some point of time, the need to pay attention to this will also be felt. I'm saying that

00:21:23.940 --> 00:21:28.500
[Guest 1]: it is easy to feel despondent because we are not heard or, I mean, people don't hear us,

00:21:28.500 --> 00:21:32.420
[Guest 1]: our voice is not being heard about. But then, at the same time, I think a time will come

00:21:32.420 --> 00:21:37.340
[Guest 1]: that they will realize that this is not working and we have to do some course correction.

00:21:37.340 --> 00:21:40.660
[Guest 1]: And so what are the ideas lying out there on the table and how much of that can be adopted?

00:21:40.660 --> 00:21:45.540
[Guest 1]: So I think, I mean, for the sake of that future optimism, we just have to keep discussing

00:21:45.540 --> 00:21:49.700
[Guest 1]: and debating and not give up. Because if we give up, that's almost like what they want

00:21:49.700 --> 00:21:52.300
[Guest 1]: us to do. And, you know, that should not happen.

00:21:52.300 --> 00:21:57.060
[Amit Varma]: So I'm just going to say, I agree with both of you. And I'm, you know, Shreyana, I find

00:21:57.060 --> 00:22:00.860
[Amit Varma]: your pessimism refreshing because when we spoke in Delhi, it's like there are two different

00:22:00.860 --> 00:22:04.340
[Amit Varma]: people, right? Shreyana comes to Delhi, she's someone else. She comes to Bombay, she's someone

00:22:04.340 --> 00:22:09.100
[Amit Varma]: else. Bombay is very, Bombay vibe is very different. I wonder what's going on, you know.

00:22:09.100 --> 00:22:16.460
[Amit Varma]: What's going on in Bombay? But there's a bandstand in Bombay.

00:22:16.460 --> 00:22:21.540
[Amit Varma]: That should make her more optimistic though. We'll come to that.

00:22:21.540 --> 00:22:26.620
[Amit Varma]: Because in Delhi, she was so optimistic that even I was saying optimistic things accidentally,

00:22:26.620 --> 00:22:30.620
[Amit Varma]: you know, just out of politeness. But I am, of course, deeply pessimistic. So I agree

00:22:30.620 --> 00:22:35.900
[Amit Varma]: with you that at one level, it can get disheartening. That okay, the rhetoric is all the same. And

00:22:35.900 --> 00:22:39.820
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned that book in which all those people had those essays. The point is, those

00:22:39.820 --> 00:22:43.580
[Guest 2]: ideas were great. They were concrete, as you point out. None of them were new. We've been

00:22:43.580 --> 00:22:48.580
[Unknown]: saying that for 20-30 years, right? You had even people like Jagdish Bhagwati and Arvind

00:22:48.580 --> 00:22:53.180
[Amit Varma]: Panagari are saying the same things. And then when they get proximity to power, just completely

00:22:53.180 --> 00:22:56.820
[Amit Varma]: ignoring everything they said and everything they believed in to go in a completely different

00:22:56.820 --> 00:23:02.340
[Amit Varma]: direction. But that is a separate rant. At the same time, Rajeshwari, I agree with you

00:23:02.340 --> 00:23:08.260
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, our words may be pointless. If I may say our, it's kind of grandiose,

00:23:08.260 --> 00:23:12.700
[Amit Varma]: but our words may be pointless. But it is in a sense our dharma to keep saying them.

00:23:12.700 --> 00:23:17.220
[Amit Varma]: Because you never really know, like one sort of interesting point Ajay Shah made with me

00:23:17.220 --> 00:23:22.820
[Amit Varma]: when he was on the show, is that he said that, look, the 91 reforms took that moment of crisis

00:23:22.820 --> 00:23:29.980
[Amit Varma]: to happen. Yes. But what is important is that there was an infrastructure of people who

00:23:29.980 --> 00:23:33.740
[Unknown]: believed in those ideas, who discussed those ideas through the mid to late 80s, which were

00:23:33.740 --> 00:23:37.580
[Amit Varma]: the economists in government and all of that. And he said that's not there anymore. Exactly.

00:23:37.580 --> 00:23:42.700
[Guest 1]: So, in fact, Amit, if I may add one point here is that we are thinking of our usefulness

00:23:42.700 --> 00:23:47.660
[Guest 1]: from a policy perspective. I think that's taking a bit of a narrow view of what economists

00:23:47.660 --> 00:23:52.860
[Guest 1]: in any field can do. Fine, maybe we are no longer a part of the Delhi North Block and

00:23:52.860 --> 00:23:56.820
[Guest 1]: South Block and whatever RBI where we used to be called at one point of time for policy

00:23:56.820 --> 00:24:02.500
[Guest 1]: discussions. But there is also a larger role that we have in terms of influencing minds

00:24:02.500 --> 00:24:08.180
[Guest 1]: and informing people, creating knowledge and diffusing knowledge. Right. So the way I look

00:24:08.180 --> 00:24:11.060
[Guest 1]: at it is, let's say you're creating knowledge or diffusing knowledge and you're trying to

00:24:11.060 --> 00:24:15.020
[Guest 1]: fix the world in whichever small teeny weeny bit you want to do it. Maybe the last part

00:24:15.020 --> 00:24:18.380
[Guest 1]: of it is a little bit broken because you don't have access to the real world policymaking

00:24:18.380 --> 00:24:23.780
[Guest 1]: process, but you still have the responsibility of creating and diffusing knowledge and diffusing

00:24:23.780 --> 00:24:29.140
[Guest 1]: ideas and then shaping people's opinions, forming opinions. For example, what I do a

00:24:29.140 --> 00:24:34.100
[Guest 1]: lot with my students, now that I'm not obviously getting engaged in the policymaking process,

00:24:34.100 --> 00:24:39.420
[Guest 1]: I engage a lot with my students because these are 21, 22 year olds and they are curious,

00:24:39.420 --> 00:24:43.580
[Guest 1]: they're hungry for knowledge. And this is my opportunity to teach them something interesting,

00:24:43.580 --> 00:24:47.740
[Guest 1]: to form their opinions, to help them debate, to provoke their thoughts. And they are the

00:24:47.740 --> 00:24:50.820
[Guest 1]: future because they are going to, after 10 years or so, they are going to turn around

00:24:50.820 --> 00:24:54.700
[Guest 1]: and say, you know, what this government is doing is not right or this is right. And to

00:24:54.700 --> 00:24:59.100
[Guest 1]: help them reach that opinion, to help them reach that kind of a knowledge is also a very

00:24:59.100 --> 00:25:02.220
[Guest 1]: big contribution that I think economists can do. And I think we should keep doing that

00:25:02.220 --> 00:25:07.700
[Guest 1]: because we will need to form that opinion. We will need to bring up that critical mass

00:25:07.700 --> 00:25:11.380
[Guest 1]: of people who believe in a certain thing. And I think that's very important, particularly

00:25:11.380 --> 00:25:15.380
[Guest 1]: now when there has been an erosion of intellectualism, if I may call it.

00:25:15.380 --> 00:25:18.740
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, I agree with you. And I just say that that's why I do the show. That's

00:25:18.740 --> 00:25:24.420
[Amit Varma]: why we write whatever we write, because the whole point is not because I'm very pessimistic.

00:25:24.420 --> 00:25:28.620
[Amit Varma]: I don't think there is an outcome to this that I might even see in my own lifetime.

00:25:28.620 --> 00:25:31.700
[Amit Varma]: But the point is you do the right thing because it is the right thing to do. Absolutely. You

00:25:31.700 --> 00:25:37.300
[Amit Varma]: don't do it with an outcome. So I can be pessimistic and still put as much of myself into the work

00:25:37.300 --> 00:25:40.180
[Amit Varma]: because I think of it as playing the long game, except it's a, you know, maybe some

00:25:40.180 --> 00:25:43.380
[Amit Varma]: 15 year old girl listening to the show today can be prime minister in 2030.

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:48.100
[Guest 1]: You're creating a community and that community may play a very important role at a time when

00:25:48.100 --> 00:25:50.820
[Amit Varma]: you may not even be around. And that's the contribution.

00:25:50.820 --> 00:25:56.500
[Amit Varma]: This specific contribution that you have mentioned is really a public intellectual facet to being

00:25:56.500 --> 00:26:01.500
[Amit Varma]: an economist. Now, you know, we took a bunch of questions on Twitter and a couple of them

00:26:01.500 --> 00:26:05.500
[Amit Varma]: and we'll come back to your personal story later. We'll keep digressing in and out. Think

00:26:05.500 --> 00:26:11.340
[Guest 1]: of it as a funky Bollywood structure. Oh, gosh. So we go in and out of different narratives.

00:26:11.340 --> 00:26:13.540
[Guest 1]: Or think of it as an adder of two and a half Bengalis.

00:26:13.540 --> 00:26:19.220
[Guest 2]: Adder of two and a half Bengalis is a great way to put it. Is you the half? I'm the half.

00:26:19.220 --> 00:26:24.940
[Guest 2]: I think it should be more like two. Yeah, I don't think I, I mean, I've just been brought

00:26:24.940 --> 00:26:29.940
[Amit Varma]: up too much in Punjab, but this is later. This is for later. So a couple of the questions

00:26:29.940 --> 00:26:34.980
[Amit Varma]: actually hit directly at this question. Like, you know, Shrena, before you came over lunch,

00:26:34.980 --> 00:26:40.780
[Amit Varma]: Rajeshwari and I were chatting about how economists often suffer from the curse of knowledge,

00:26:40.780 --> 00:26:44.220
[Amit Varma]: that they'll know something so well that they'll assume that, oh, everybody knows this, we

00:26:44.220 --> 00:26:48.100
[Amit Varma]: don't need to say it. And I realized sometimes it's not the case. Most people really want

00:26:48.100 --> 00:26:51.620
[Amit Varma]: to know, they're curious about what do economists do. And a couple of the questions that came

00:26:51.620 --> 00:26:58.620
[Amit Varma]: in indicate that. Where Monami at Monami DG on Twitter asks, how has their research contributed

00:26:58.620 --> 00:27:04.400
[Amit Varma]: to or influence real change in the society? Right? That's one thing. And another question

00:27:04.400 --> 00:27:09.720
[Amit Varma]: from Murugesh is, in which area, the theory of economics has the highest accuracy or probability

00:27:09.720 --> 00:27:15.100
[Amit Varma]: of success? That's another thing. And there are different questions, you know, a couple

00:27:15.100 --> 00:27:20.940
[Amit Varma]: of the lovely sort of sceptical notes that were struck. One is by Varun Das, where he

00:27:20.940 --> 00:27:25.500
[Amit Varma]: paraphrased George Bernard Shaw. And he said, lay them end to end and see if they reach

00:27:25.500 --> 00:27:30.320
[Amit Varma]: a conclusion. And another one, you know, Harry Truman had this famous saying, I want a one

00:27:30.320 --> 00:27:34.420
[Amit Varma]: handed economist, because economists keep saying on one hand this on the other. And

00:27:34.420 --> 00:27:38.420
[Amit Varma]: a Twitter user called up to a point asked the question, would an octopus make for a

00:27:38.420 --> 00:27:45.220
[Amit Varma]: good economist? Because it can say on the other hand, seven times. But my entirely serious

00:27:45.220 --> 00:27:51.220
[Amit Varma]: question there for a layperson is what do economists do? Right? Now, one of the laments

00:27:51.220 --> 00:27:56.420
[Amit Varma]: of our friend Ajay has been that too many economists who have studied the subject and

00:27:56.420 --> 00:28:00.940
[Amit Varma]: know the subject, then enter this long academic circle jerk where they take themselves out

00:28:00.940 --> 00:28:04.820
[Amit Varma]: of the system, and they have no impact at all on the real world. And it is his lament

00:28:04.820 --> 00:28:09.260
[Amit Varma]: that too many bright people do this, and more people should stay back like him, who actually

00:28:09.260 --> 00:28:15.140
[Amit Varma]: try to make, who actually try to do things in the real world. Now, where do you find

00:28:15.140 --> 00:28:19.100
[Amit Varma]: economists? You know, like, in Delhi, I understand there might be places you can throw a stone

00:28:19.100 --> 00:28:24.180
[Amit Varma]: and hit one. But not that economists should be strong. No, but they might be. They might

00:28:24.180 --> 00:28:31.660
[Amit Varma]: be strong. Very, very, very soon in multiple ways. But so tell me, what is the ecosystem

00:28:31.660 --> 00:28:35.340
[Amit Varma]: for economists? Like, where are economists? What are they doing? Do they make a difference

00:28:35.340 --> 00:28:42.060
[Guest 1]: in the real world? So, if I may go first, which is, so there was a time Amit when and

00:28:42.060 --> 00:28:45.940
[Guest 1]: I'm talking of let's say in pre 90s, right? When you think of economists or statisticians,

00:28:45.940 --> 00:28:51.300
[Guest 1]: they were all in academia, right? You would have this universities and they would be professors,

00:28:51.300 --> 00:28:55.380
[Guest 1]: faculty members teaching students and doing research. This was the old traditional world

00:28:55.380 --> 00:29:01.660
[Guest 1]: of economists. From there, we went through liberalization, privatization, globalization,

00:29:01.660 --> 00:29:06.780
[Guest 1]: etc. And then I think the whole ecosystem of economists where they can go broadened

00:29:06.780 --> 00:29:11.780
[Guest 1]: significantly and it's no longer just limited to academic economists going to university

00:29:11.780 --> 00:29:15.500
[Guest 1]: teaching students and writing research papers that nobody can understand. A lot of that

00:29:15.500 --> 00:29:19.940
[Guest 1]: happens as well. At the same time, for example, you have think tanks and this started with

00:29:19.940 --> 00:29:24.420
[Guest 1]: the planning commission being the oldest think tank, so to speak, planning commission and

00:29:24.420 --> 00:29:27.740
[Guest 1]: from there on you think of all the think tanks in Delhi, Bangalore, Bombay, Pune, all over

00:29:27.740 --> 00:29:31.660
[Guest 1]: the place in India and globally as well. Where these are the economists have chosen not to

00:29:31.660 --> 00:29:36.180
[Guest 1]: enter universities, you're not essentially teaching students per se, but you're doing

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:40.300
[Guest 1]: a lot of government work, you're doing a lot of policy work, which is also very valuable.

00:29:40.300 --> 00:29:45.060
[Guest 1]: Also, then there are a lot of economists who are in demand in the corporate world. So,

00:29:45.060 --> 00:29:48.620
[Guest 1]: all of these big corporate banks, corporate organizations would have chief economists

00:29:48.620 --> 00:29:52.700
[Guest 1]: and other economists positions where they need this economist to talk to the foreign

00:29:52.700 --> 00:29:57.260
[Guest 1]: clientele, foreign investors, domestic investors as well and that's a good service because

00:29:57.260 --> 00:30:01.900
[Guest 1]: you are sort of convincing the investors to bring money into India, you're convincing

00:30:01.900 --> 00:30:05.940
[Guest 1]: the domestic investors to invest in a certain financial portfolio and you're sort of helping

00:30:05.940 --> 00:30:09.940
[Guest 1]: them understand what the economy, what's the state of the economy like. And that's also

00:30:09.940 --> 00:30:13.820
[Guest 1]: I think a very important thing that they're doing. And also, for example, you would have

00:30:13.820 --> 00:30:19.380
[Guest 1]: economists in India particularly, where there is this mix of you are an academic economist

00:30:19.380 --> 00:30:25.900
[Guest 1]: who are in a university, you're teaching students, etc. But you're also involved in media writing

00:30:25.900 --> 00:30:30.740
[Guest 1]: where you want to make economics more accessible to the common man and you're writing in media

00:30:30.740 --> 00:30:35.420
[Guest 1]: on a regular basis because you feel strongly about these things, you think that you need

00:30:35.420 --> 00:30:39.180
[Guest 1]: to have a voice and the common man and these are newspapers or media outlets that are being

00:30:39.180 --> 00:30:44.220
[Guest 1]: accessed by educated people, let's call it that way. And therefore, you are no longer

00:30:44.220 --> 00:30:48.620
[Guest 1]: keeping economics restricted to only those who understand the jargon, the math, the numbers,

00:30:48.620 --> 00:30:52.260
[Guest 1]: you're trying to make it accessible, which I think is extremely important. And these

00:30:52.260 --> 00:30:56.100
[Guest 1]: are also the economists who could equationally engage with think tanks, occasionally engaging

00:30:56.100 --> 00:31:00.060
[Guest 1]: with the consulting world, with the corporate world. And then there's sort of the boundaries

00:31:00.060 --> 00:31:04.300
[Guest 1]: get blurred, which I find is a fascinating development that has happened in this post

00:31:04.300 --> 00:31:09.220
[Guest 1]: liberalization world, which was non-existent earlier. So that economists operating in silos

00:31:09.220 --> 00:31:13.860
[Guest 1]: or economists sitting in ivory towers and completely inaccessible to the common man,

00:31:13.860 --> 00:31:18.580
[Guest 1]: I think that has definitely changed significantly. And it's something to be quite hopeful about.

00:31:18.580 --> 00:31:25.340
[Guest 1]: For example, I look at my coterie of economies that I hang out with, so to speak, almost

00:31:25.340 --> 00:31:30.620
[Guest 1]: nobody is an academic economist in university, right? Everybody, either they have their entrepreneurs

00:31:30.620 --> 00:31:35.100
[Guest 1]: have started their own think tank, or they are in a corporate world where, you know,

00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:39.660
[Guest 1]: talking to investors and writing regularly in columns, they are writing chapters in books,

00:31:39.660 --> 00:31:43.580
[Guest 1]: they are talking to multilateral organizations, it's all over the place. So the contribution

00:31:43.580 --> 00:31:47.220
[Guest 1]: is no longer that one centric that either you're teaching students and sitting in ivory

00:31:47.220 --> 00:31:52.540
[Guest 1]: tower, or you're sitting in a planning commission. It's a much more broad based contribution.

00:31:52.540 --> 00:31:56.300
[Guest 1]: And that's why I think that we shouldn't only think of our usefulness from a policymaking

00:31:56.300 --> 00:32:01.140
[Guest 1]: perspective. Even if that one thing has gotten suppressed for the time being, there are many,

00:32:01.140 --> 00:32:05.180
[Guest 1]: many other things where you could be contributing. And I guess that's what to answer your question.

00:32:05.180 --> 00:32:07.420
[Guest 2]: That's what economists do.

00:32:07.420 --> 00:32:11.900
[Guest 2]: Maybe I can come in, you know, in fact, this relates to what I was also talking about the

00:32:11.900 --> 00:32:17.860
[Guest 2]: general sense of despondency. First, let's start with who is an economist, right? Like,

00:32:17.860 --> 00:32:22.460
[Guest 2]: let's just start with that. I completely disagree. I don't have a PhD in economics. I have a

00:32:22.460 --> 00:32:27.780
[Guest 2]: job. It's very much a job of a jobbing economist. I work with people at the World Bank, many

00:32:27.780 --> 00:32:33.100
[Guest 2]: of them come from very strong, almost jobbing every day dealing with the economy and real

00:32:33.100 --> 00:32:37.660
[Guest 2]: terms in very different ways. Some work on infrastructure, some may work on tariff pricing,

00:32:37.660 --> 00:32:43.060
[Guest 2]: some work like myself on the welfare state. So let's start with that. I think the biggest

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:48.460
[Guest 2]: issue I take with I think the economist community is while I agree with Rajeshwari that there's

00:32:48.460 --> 00:32:53.560
[Guest 2]: a blurring, but I think there's a blurring as long as you have the same sort of status

00:32:53.560 --> 00:32:57.980
[Guest 2]: and credentials as each other. You can speak to each other, you can almost scan your CVs

00:32:57.980 --> 00:33:02.620
[Guest 2]: and you have a sense of what that means. There are lots of economists and young students

00:33:02.620 --> 00:33:08.300
[Guest 2]: who studied economics. I go to Bhubaneswar, I go to like small towns in Chhattisgarh.

00:33:08.300 --> 00:33:13.420
[Guest 2]: There are kids who have studied a master's who are interested. Some of them have joined

00:33:13.420 --> 00:33:18.520
[Guest 2]: junior government services, right? So they are state carder officers. There are lots

00:33:18.520 --> 00:33:23.900
[Guest 2]: of people who are very elegant in the way they think about using economic theory data.

00:33:23.900 --> 00:33:28.700
[Guest 2]: They have a great facility for it. They may not have PhDs from the fanciest places or

00:33:28.700 --> 00:33:33.100
[Guest 2]: they may not be in fact interacting with the world of status, be it think tanks, corporate,

00:33:33.100 --> 00:33:38.860
[Guest 2]: so on and so forth. But they are actively using that body of knowledge in their everyday

00:33:38.860 --> 00:33:43.360
[Guest 2]: decision making. I work with some of these young men. Often they are men. That is still

00:33:43.360 --> 00:33:46.740
[Guest 2]: the nature of I think that's the other thing. One is who is an economist and economist is

00:33:46.740 --> 00:33:53.700
[Guest 2]: often a man. So it's really lovely that actually we're both here. So thanks Amit for that.

00:33:53.700 --> 00:33:57.980
[Guest 2]: And I think the first issue we do have to sort of start to think about and I think Amit

00:33:57.980 --> 00:34:02.540
[Guest 2]: you and I talked about it during our last episode, which is how do you start to create

00:34:02.540 --> 00:34:10.260
[Guest 2]: a community of thinking and practice around the economy that may not necessarily be involved

00:34:10.260 --> 00:34:19.180
[Guest 2]: in academic production or production of research material for policymaking or for essentially

00:34:19.180 --> 00:34:24.120
[Guest 2]: communicating to a future generation of students because I think that's a very different world.

00:34:24.120 --> 00:34:28.500
[Guest 2]: We also talked about last time, Amit, that the point is not to impact policy. The point

00:34:28.500 --> 00:34:32.580
[Guest 2]: is to change the way people think. And I think economic theory actually, perhaps sometimes

00:34:32.580 --> 00:34:37.780
[Guest 2]: even more than data, has a very strong way of helping you make sense of the world. And

00:34:37.780 --> 00:34:41.540
[Guest 2]: I see that. So I think the first thing I want to say is, you know, when you ask what do

00:34:41.540 --> 00:34:44.900
[Guest 2]: economists do, I think the first thing we need to ask is who is an economist? And to

00:34:44.900 --> 00:34:49.820
[Guest 2]: me an economist is not someone who just has a PhD from a certain set of schools who studied

00:34:49.820 --> 00:34:53.180
[Guest 2]: it. People who have that obviously have a very, they play in a different league and

00:34:53.180 --> 00:34:57.900
[Guest 2]: I think that's a different world. But there's a whole community out there who I don't think

00:34:57.900 --> 00:35:03.980
[Guest 2]: are as vociferous and I wish they were. And I'm looking to that. And what makes me despondent

00:35:03.980 --> 00:35:08.660
[Guest 2]: honestly is when you asked what do economists do? So there's the world that Rajeshwari just

00:35:08.660 --> 00:35:14.420
[Guest 2]: described, which is actually I do agree is thriving. There's a lot of investment. This

00:35:14.420 --> 00:35:19.180
[Guest 2]: is being supported. You start to move away. And in fact, there are think tanks which used

00:35:19.180 --> 00:35:25.100
[Guest 2]: to be really well supported now are struggling with FCRA, raising domestic funding, raising

00:35:25.100 --> 00:35:30.500
[Guest 2]: foreign funding for research. And I think there's a deep crisis of that. And when I'm

00:35:30.500 --> 00:35:35.460
[Guest 2]: talking about these young men, they are again, I hope there'll be more young women in say,

00:35:35.460 --> 00:35:41.660
[Guest 2]: you know, a small town or tier two town in a state in India, which is not Maharashtra

00:35:41.660 --> 00:35:47.660
[Guest 2]: or Delhi. I think part of the issue is where will the financing, a sustainable model of

00:35:47.660 --> 00:35:53.700
[Guest 2]: financing come from where a lot of these young men and women can be exposed to economic models

00:35:53.700 --> 00:35:59.420
[Guest 2]: of thinking, which I think are really powerful, and then use them in their day to day lives

00:35:59.420 --> 00:36:03.260
[Guest 2]: almost as if, you know, you're solving puzzles, which is actually sometimes what I think is

00:36:03.260 --> 00:36:08.460
[Guest 2]: very elegant about the subject. I don't think we're doing that enough. I think what economists

00:36:08.460 --> 00:36:13.620
[Guest 2]: tend to do is, Rajeshwari, I think has just summarized that really beautifully. Just from

00:36:13.620 --> 00:36:19.100
[Guest 2]: my own example, day to day, what is my job? My job is, in fact, using a lot of that theory

00:36:19.100 --> 00:36:24.820
[Guest 2]: to think about how different states in India design their welfare policies. How is the

00:36:24.820 --> 00:36:29.380
[Guest 2]: welfare state functioning? In fact, I think one of the core areas where I think economists

00:36:29.380 --> 00:36:33.900
[Guest 2]: and economists who don't necessarily, again, subscribe to a certain way we define economists

00:36:33.900 --> 00:36:39.420
[Guest 2]: have really impacted the real world is welfare. I think Rajeshwari alluded to this, so many

00:36:39.420 --> 00:36:44.780
[Guest 2]: NGOs, so many activists, actually, they come from the world of partial economics training,

00:36:44.780 --> 00:36:49.780
[Guest 2]: and I can see how they've used those ideas, a kind of affinity to evidence based decision

00:36:49.780 --> 00:36:55.580
[Guest 2]: making in their activism, which has been really powerful. And I think, you know, we owe a

00:36:55.580 --> 00:37:03.380
[Guest 2]: lot to that. And I think what we need to think very carefully about as a community is how

00:37:03.380 --> 00:37:11.900
[Guest 2]: is it that we can raise support and create a parallel ecosystem, which actually supports

00:37:11.900 --> 00:37:17.860
[Guest 2]: this kind of knowledge generation, access to data, and it doesn't ring fence it around

00:37:17.860 --> 00:37:23.100
[Guest 2]: just certain norms around what is considered sort of, you know, who is an economist by

00:37:23.100 --> 00:37:28.420
[Guest 2]: status, but who is an economist by interest and by activity. And then, you know, you may

00:37:28.420 --> 00:37:32.300
[Guest 2]: really be terrible at the subject, like I could never finish a PhD, it's just not, I

00:37:32.300 --> 00:37:36.220
[Guest 2]: don't have the talent or the tenacity for it. As I mentioned earlier, I have different

00:37:36.220 --> 00:37:41.380
[Guest 2]: kinds of talents. And that actually is a world, Amit, I'm very optimistic about. I think for

00:37:41.380 --> 00:37:46.220
[Guest 2]: me, maybe that is where moving away what I will do in the future, I think that is where

00:37:46.220 --> 00:37:51.940
[Guest 2]: I'm interested. But if you start to look at what's happening to that world now, it's institutionally

00:37:51.940 --> 00:37:58.100
[Guest 2]: heavily constrained in terms of where it will find sources of just straight up market financing

00:37:58.100 --> 00:38:03.740
[Guest 2]: to support it. You have, you know, I can tell you there are IES officers or state carder

00:38:03.740 --> 00:38:08.580
[Guest 2]: officers working in different states in the country who want to be better trained. They

00:38:08.580 --> 00:38:13.980
[Guest 2]: want to study more, they want to learn more. But the Indian Labasna and all the sort of,

00:38:13.980 --> 00:38:20.300
[Guest 2]: you know, the institutions that teach theory or practice to these, you know, to officers,

00:38:20.300 --> 00:38:24.100
[Guest 2]: they are limited in also what they are able to do and who they will include in their training

00:38:24.100 --> 00:38:27.820
[Guest 2]: programs, the capacity, and I think you had guests here who've talked about this before,

00:38:27.820 --> 00:38:33.260
[Guest 2]: the capacity of administrative structures to offer this kind of training is also limited.

00:38:33.260 --> 00:38:38.380
[Guest 2]: Star economists do not go to, you know, small state carder training academies to sort of

00:38:38.380 --> 00:38:41.980
[Guest 2]: train. I think that's starting to change. I'm very excited by some of the things I hear

00:38:41.980 --> 00:38:47.580
[Guest 2]: J-PAL is trying to do with their partnerships. I think that's really the space where I think

00:38:47.580 --> 00:38:53.980
[Guest 2]: economists, there's a lot of demand for economists to do stuff. And I think there could be buoyancy.

00:38:53.980 --> 00:38:57.860
[Guest 2]: But right now, it's heavily constrained. And I think to answer your question, in addition

00:38:57.860 --> 00:39:00.700
[Guest 2]: to I think what Rajeshree said and the question the gentleman asked about what do economists

00:39:00.700 --> 00:39:07.300
[Guest 2]: do, I also think economists do participate, we can't walk away from the circle jerk. That

00:39:07.300 --> 00:39:13.420
[Guest 2]: is a significant chunk of what I think a lot of economists are doing. And I face it and

00:39:13.420 --> 00:39:16.220
[Guest 2]: you know, I've seen it, it's interesting, even with the book of the life of the book,

00:39:16.220 --> 00:39:21.420
[Guest 2]: I've noticed what that actually means. And I think being a bit more empathetic to the

00:39:21.420 --> 00:39:25.300
[Guest 2]: fact that there's a community out there that may not be participating in the circle jerk,

00:39:25.300 --> 00:39:31.220
[Guest 2]: but is very interested, and is also in positions of authority and power, and also in their

00:39:31.220 --> 00:39:37.540
[Guest 2]: day to day life can use this as theory data and make impactful, meaningful decisions.

00:39:37.540 --> 00:39:40.940
[Guest 2]: I think that's really critical to me. So yeah.

00:39:40.940 --> 00:39:44.980
[Guest 1]: One thing if I may add Amit is, it may not have come across clearly, but one thing that

00:39:44.980 --> 00:39:50.580
[Guest 1]: I was trying to allude to is that there was a time when economics was considered an inaccessible

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:57.220
[Guest 1]: subject. Because it is traditionally very math heavy. It was more science than social

00:39:57.220 --> 00:40:04.340
[Guest 1]: science. It was very heavy in statistics. It was considered that only a handful of people

00:40:04.340 --> 00:40:09.300
[Guest 1]: who have a certain knowledge or bent of mind and access to a certain kind of training can

00:40:09.300 --> 00:40:15.100
[Guest 1]: end up studying economics. And that limited the scope for economics. And that also, I

00:40:15.100 --> 00:40:19.540
[Guest 1]: think, gave economics a bad name down the road. Because, you know, there's this notion

00:40:19.540 --> 00:40:24.020
[Guest 1]: that if you're an economist, it's a very hard subject, it's a very dry thing, we are dealing

00:40:24.020 --> 00:40:27.820
[Guest 1]: with things that we don't even understand. At the same time, economics fundamentally

00:40:27.820 --> 00:40:33.220
[Guest 1]: at heart is a social science, right? It derives inspiration from what's happening in the society.

00:40:33.220 --> 00:40:37.380
[Guest 1]: And therefore, I think somewhere down the line, we lost that connection that economists

00:40:37.380 --> 00:40:41.380
[Guest 1]: need to be able to explain what's happening in the society and also communicate that to

00:40:41.380 --> 00:40:47.740
[Guest 1]: the society. So we went into this whole world of almost every scientific theorizing world

00:40:47.740 --> 00:40:52.380
[Guest 1]: where you're very good in your theoretical models, and you're doing a whole lot of cranking

00:40:52.380 --> 00:40:57.740
[Guest 1]: of equations and math. But ultimately, what does it all mean in terms of intuition in

00:40:57.740 --> 00:41:01.380
[Guest 1]: terms of the real life social impact, and very, very few economists would then make

00:41:01.380 --> 00:41:06.220
[Guest 1]: the effort of bridging that gap. And I think, primarily in the US, for example, where most

00:41:06.220 --> 00:41:10.780
[Guest 1]: of the economic theories come from, a lot of it was because economists there is all

00:41:10.780 --> 00:41:15.740
[Guest 1]: university economist, with PhD, as Shaina mentioned, publishing in journals. So that's

00:41:15.740 --> 00:41:19.980
[Guest 1]: a whole different ballgame altogether. But what I what I realized is, and I think I've

00:41:19.980 --> 00:41:25.260
[Guest 1]: mentioned in the first episode with you is that when I came back to India, I realized

00:41:25.260 --> 00:41:30.860
[Guest 1]: the world is much very, very different and, and much better, quote, unquote, compared

00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:35.500
[Guest 1]: to what I saw in the US, because here there are economists who make the effort to reach

00:41:35.500 --> 00:41:39.780
[Guest 1]: out to the common man or beat. And this has nothing to do with whether you have a PhD

00:41:39.780 --> 00:41:43.220
[Guest 1]: in economics, when you don't have a PhD in economics, you have some basic training in

00:41:43.220 --> 00:41:45.820
[Guest 1]: economics, you understand the world, and you want to explain the world to the rest of the

00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:49.940
[Guest 1]: society. And there are people have made that effort, you're writing in the media, you're,

00:41:49.940 --> 00:41:53.820
[Guest 1]: you're doing, you know, even to the extent that everybody listens to TV, even in regional

00:41:53.820 --> 00:41:57.020
[Guest 1]: languages, right, you're doing TV interviews, you're trying to explain what the budget means,

00:41:57.020 --> 00:42:00.700
[Guest 1]: you're trying to explain what's happening to inflation, what's happening to prices.

00:42:00.700 --> 00:42:04.540
[Guest 1]: And that is very, very important. And I think that's a very valuable service that economists

00:42:04.540 --> 00:42:08.260
[Guest 1]: and by economists, I mean, anybody who has a basic training in economics to be able to

00:42:08.260 --> 00:42:11.740
[Guest 1]: understand things a little bit better than let's say, for example, what the common man

00:42:11.740 --> 00:42:16.580
[Guest 1]: on the street would, but they are taking that effort to explain that. And to and that is

00:42:16.580 --> 00:42:20.660
[Guest 1]: a world that I think has happened over the last 20, 30 years. And of course, there's

00:42:20.660 --> 00:42:25.860
[Guest 1]: a whole long way to go, we are just only scratching the surface. But to the extent that it is

00:42:25.860 --> 00:42:30.380
[Guest 1]: happening to the extent that people there is a critical mass of economists are at least

00:42:30.380 --> 00:42:34.060
[Guest 1]: aware of this responsibility, and they're doing it, doing that, I think that that's

00:42:34.060 --> 00:42:39.620
[Guest 1]: definitely a great thing. And in terms of funding, I think, this is a constraint across

00:42:39.620 --> 00:42:44.740
[Guest 1]: all subjects, like even hard sciences, which traditionally would get more funding. Everybody's

00:42:44.740 --> 00:42:49.740
[Guest 1]: struggling to get funding over the last few years, because there is this whole, like constraint

00:42:49.740 --> 00:42:55.780
[Guest 1]: on intellectual pursuit or constraint on scientific pursuit, in terms of giving funding to universities

00:42:55.780 --> 00:42:56.780
[Guest 1]: and institutions.

00:42:56.780 --> 00:43:00.820
[Guest 2]: Can I just, I just want to just on one thing, I don't, in fact, I think that there has been

00:43:00.820 --> 00:43:05.420
[Guest 2]: a particular squeeze put in and maybe Amit also, I think part of my pessimism is coming

00:43:05.420 --> 00:43:09.780
[Guest 2]: from, I've just come back from Delhi, and I've seen some very dear friends who are trying

00:43:09.780 --> 00:43:17.380
[Guest 2]: to just hold on to their organizations, with dear life, it's very hard right now, especially

00:43:17.380 --> 00:43:23.180
[Guest 2]: if you're going to produce independent social science research, which invariably will speak

00:43:23.180 --> 00:43:30.140
[Guest 2]: to livelihoods. I see this across the board. In fact, some of the most useful economic

00:43:30.140 --> 00:43:36.300
[Guest 2]: data is coming out of NGOs that, you know, you take Ajivika Bureau, looking at migrants,

00:43:36.300 --> 00:43:39.980
[Guest 2]: you look at a lot of the work that's coming out of different organizations, who are not

00:43:39.980 --> 00:43:44.340
[Guest 2]: even based in Delhi or Bombay, they're not interested in that game. They are all being

00:43:44.340 --> 00:43:48.980
[Guest 2]: squeezed. It's a very difficult time. And I think, while yes, sure, it's difficult for

00:43:48.980 --> 00:43:53.020
[Guest 2]: universities and institutions, but universities and institutions will always fight. There'll

00:43:53.020 --> 00:43:58.740
[Guest 2]: be corporates, there'll be, you know, patrons, there'll be alumni. When I look at these organizations,

00:43:58.740 --> 00:44:03.820
[Guest 2]: which are almost trying to create their own models of economic investigation, actually,

00:44:03.820 --> 00:44:08.060
[Guest 2]: a lot of theory is ground up theory, right? It can come from here. I think they can come

00:44:08.060 --> 00:44:11.480
[Guest 2]: up with a very different way of thinking about how we theorize migration movements and labor

00:44:11.480 --> 00:44:16.940
[Guest 2]: leisure trade-offs, for example, but who will finance that work? Because what I see, and

00:44:16.940 --> 00:44:22.900
[Guest 2]: you know, maybe this comes from the fact that my first job ever was at a heavily underfunded

00:44:22.900 --> 00:44:29.060
[Guest 2]: feminist think tank, where I saw my boss constantly struggling, this remarkable woman constantly

00:44:29.060 --> 00:44:34.980
[Guest 2]: struggling to just organize funds. And invariably, if you link yourself to donor financing, which

00:44:34.980 --> 00:44:40.980
[Guest 2]: is invariably what happens with think tanks, livelihoods organizations, donors are interested

00:44:40.980 --> 00:44:45.220
[Guest 2]: and I don't blame them. I understand they're interested in certain outcomes, right? Which

00:44:45.220 --> 00:44:50.420
[Guest 2]: always have to do with, give me a survey, give me some data points. But maybe there's

00:44:50.420 --> 00:44:55.940
[Guest 2]: theory that can be built off that. There are lessons to be crystallized. And I just don't

00:44:55.940 --> 00:45:01.180
[Guest 2]: see right now, and I see organizations really struggling to find core institutional funding

00:45:01.180 --> 00:45:06.340
[Guest 2]: to be able to do that. And I think in that world, you will still have the dominant modes

00:45:06.340 --> 00:45:11.140
[Guest 2]: of knowledge production, particularly in the social sciences and economics is particularly

00:45:11.140 --> 00:45:16.140
[Guest 2]: politically very important because it is the economy, right? I mean, it kind of holds a

00:45:16.140 --> 00:45:23.100
[Guest 2]: set of interactions, which hold tremendous power. And I think I see that. So I share,

00:45:23.100 --> 00:45:27.740
[Guest 2]: I think what Rajeshwari says that, well, things have changed and that, you know, it's a much

00:45:27.740 --> 00:45:33.660
[Guest 2]: more democratic space. Sure. I think there's a lot more than we can do. I often joke now

00:45:33.660 --> 00:45:39.580
[Guest 2]: that I don't want to Brahmin explain the economy to anyone. I actually now just want to hear

00:45:39.580 --> 00:45:44.100
[Guest 2]: where different theories come from. And I think there are things happening in universities

00:45:44.100 --> 00:45:51.060
[Guest 2]: we may not even know about, right? Or organizations we may not know of. But what often I wonder

00:45:51.060 --> 00:45:54.820
[Guest 2]: about is where will that almost the venture capital for that come from? And in fact, this

00:45:54.820 --> 00:45:59.620
[Guest 2]: is where I think that the Indian private sector can come into play a really important role

00:45:59.620 --> 00:46:03.780
[Guest 2]: because we know these organizations are going to struggle to find foreign financing. So

00:46:03.780 --> 00:46:08.540
[Guest 2]: yeah, I think we have to think about just these very alternative models of supporting

00:46:08.540 --> 00:46:12.500
[Guest 2]: these ecosystems. And that I think I'm very excited about because I do think that there

00:46:12.500 --> 00:46:16.780
[Guest 2]: is a quorum of now young people, particularly in the private sector, who I think are thinking

00:46:16.780 --> 00:46:21.100
[Guest 2]: about some of these things, especially given where we are right now as a country.

00:46:21.100 --> 00:46:24.980
[Guest 1]: So I'll tell you that the peculiar thing that happens with the funding constraint, and this

00:46:24.980 --> 00:46:30.900
[Guest 1]: I again learned after coming back here, is that there are certain fields which are fundable

00:46:30.900 --> 00:46:35.620
[Guest 1]: and then certain fields will not attract funding no matter what you do. And unfortunately,

00:46:35.620 --> 00:46:42.060
[Guest 1]: because I do macroeconomics, it is one of the unfundable fields, right? Nobody is interested.

00:46:42.060 --> 00:46:46.660
[Guest 1]: Nobody's interested in understanding GDP growth rate, but nobody's interested in funding any

00:46:46.660 --> 00:46:51.380
[Guest 1]: effort to actually understand the data collection process, right? Everybody's interested in

00:46:51.380 --> 00:46:56.260
[Guest 1]: inflation because it affects the common man, but nobody, none of the donors is interested

00:46:56.260 --> 00:47:01.100
[Guest 1]: in anything to do with funding monetary policy research. Everybody's interested in government

00:47:01.100 --> 00:47:06.020
[Guest 1]: debt taxation. Nobody's interested in funding research to do with the fiscal policies of

00:47:06.020 --> 00:47:10.980
[Guest 1]: the government. So I unfortunately work in a field where there is no scope to get funding

00:47:10.980 --> 00:47:15.820
[Guest 1]: from anybody, right? Be it the big global multilateral organizations, be it the private

00:47:15.820 --> 00:47:20.900
[Guest 1]: sector, be it anybody, right? And I woke up to this reality and I realized that while

00:47:20.900 --> 00:47:26.140
[Guest 1]: I am at an institute where there is some funding coming from X, Y, Z, but there is also a push

00:47:26.140 --> 00:47:30.580
[Guest 1]: to become more independent in terms of funding. So let's say, for example, if I want to start

00:47:30.580 --> 00:47:35.460
[Guest 1]: my own center in macroeconomics research, I will never be able to get funding from anybody

00:47:35.460 --> 00:47:39.300
[Guest 1]: despite the fact that I want to start the center in the university. And the university

00:47:39.300 --> 00:47:42.660
[Guest 1]: itself doesn't want to do the funding. That's the whole idea of starting an autonomous center,

00:47:42.660 --> 00:47:45.980
[Guest 1]: but I won't get funding. But then what do I have to do? If I want to get funding, I'll

00:47:45.980 --> 00:47:50.900
[Guest 1]: have to change my areas of interest. I have to change my specialization. So for example,

00:47:50.900 --> 00:47:55.740
[Guest 1]: if I start working on climate change, if I start working even on any topic related to

00:47:55.740 --> 00:48:00.860
[Guest 1]: development economics, if I start working on renewable energy, right? These are the

00:48:00.860 --> 00:48:05.620
[Guest 1]: fundable fields where at least there is some scope of getting funding, consumer protection

00:48:05.620 --> 00:48:09.580
[Guest 1]: in finance. These are the silos where you can at least get some funding. So then you

00:48:09.580 --> 00:48:14.180
[Guest 1]: start to think that, okay, if I want to stay true to what I understand, what I have a limited

00:48:14.180 --> 00:48:18.580
[Guest 1]: training and I'm passionate about that, then how do I get my own independent funding if

00:48:18.580 --> 00:48:22.500
[Guest 1]: I want to hire five RAs who are equally interested in these subjects and I want to pay their

00:48:22.500 --> 00:48:26.740
[Guest 1]: salaries, where will I get the money from? But then does that mean I have to now start

00:48:26.740 --> 00:48:32.060
[Guest 1]: researching in climate change, renewables, health, wherever the donors and the funders

00:48:32.060 --> 00:48:36.860
[Guest 1]: think that they are going to get high returns from, right? So that becomes the distortion

00:48:36.860 --> 00:48:42.700
[Guest 1]: in social sciences like economics where either you change your field to suit the donor and

00:48:42.700 --> 00:48:47.860
[Guest 1]: the funder or you languish in this low-level equilibrium where your salary is just being

00:48:47.860 --> 00:48:51.820
[Guest 1]: given by the university, but that may not be enough because a lot of constraints imposed

00:48:51.820 --> 00:48:56.400
[Guest 1]: on you by the institute and you may not be having the independence to start a center

00:48:56.400 --> 00:49:01.820
[Guest 1]: of your own where you can hire RAs, etc. So it's a very, very difficult world to negotiate.

00:49:01.820 --> 00:49:03.220
[Guest 1]: There is no doubt about that.

00:49:03.220 --> 00:49:06.900
[Amit Varma]: So a few strands I want to pick up on and I'll come back to funding, but first we'll

00:49:06.900 --> 00:49:11.260
[Amit Varma]: kind of circle around the globe and sort of do that. And one is one of my constant rants

00:49:11.260 --> 00:49:15.780
[Amit Varma]: on the show is this impression people have that economics has nothing to do with the

00:49:15.780 --> 00:49:20.820
[Amit Varma]: real world. Who cares about these numbers and what is GDP anyway and this and that.

00:49:20.820 --> 00:49:23.780
[Amit Varma]: And by the way, there were many questions on the GDP for us on Twitter and I just want

00:49:23.780 --> 00:49:27.940
[Amit Varma]: to tell all of them that listen, you have an episode length answer on that because Rajeshwari

00:49:27.940 --> 00:49:32.860
[Amit Varma]: and I did a long episode on GDP, which goes into all of these issues. Why is women's unpaid

00:49:32.860 --> 00:49:37.460
[Amit Varma]: labor not counted? And so many conceptual problems with the GDP, practical problems

00:49:37.460 --> 00:49:42.660
[Amit Varma]: with the GDP and so on and so forth. But my point always has been that numbers are people

00:49:42.660 --> 00:49:49.100
[Amit Varma]: too. That, you know, economics matters because it shines a lens on real things going wrong

00:49:49.100 --> 00:49:55.420
[Amit Varma]: in the real world to real people. A good economist will always make that distinction clear. Like

00:49:55.420 --> 00:49:59.860
[Amit Varma]: one of the reasons I loved your book Shrayana so much was that's exactly what you did, right?

00:49:59.860 --> 00:50:04.700
[Amit Varma]: You used the tools of economics, the frames of economics of thinking about problems to

00:50:04.700 --> 00:50:09.820
[Amit Varma]: get to, in a sense, the core of the human condition, that this is what people are like.

00:50:09.820 --> 00:50:13.180
[Amit Varma]: This is why a man and a woman in the same house can't speak, which is a great human

00:50:13.180 --> 00:50:18.740
[Amit Varma]: tragedy. But this is why it is and you're using those tools to illuminate that, you

00:50:18.740 --> 00:50:25.140
[Amit Varma]: know. And to me, that's the best of economics in the sense that it's okay. I see this entire

00:50:25.140 --> 00:50:30.100
[Amit Varma]: class of economists who go to college, get their PhDs, get all of that. They'll be hyper

00:50:30.100 --> 00:50:35.100
[Amit Varma]: specialized in sea trade between Peru and Bolivia between 1830 to 1844, right?

00:50:35.100 --> 00:50:42.300
[Amit Varma]: I know who you're talking about. No, I'm not actually talking about anyone in particular.

00:50:42.300 --> 00:50:47.100
[Amit Varma]: I never, I never, I never, I don't. It is my job to introduce the gossip into the, we'll

00:50:47.100 --> 00:50:51.260
[Amit Varma]: come to that. We'll come to that. But on the other hand, the thing about economics and

00:50:51.260 --> 00:50:55.780
[Amit Varma]: why I am so much in love with it, and of course, I don't have a PhD in it either. But one reason

00:50:55.780 --> 00:51:02.340
[Amit Varma]: I love economics is I feel economics fundamentally is a study of human behavior, right? So if

00:51:02.340 --> 00:51:07.580
[Amit Varma]: you're interested in human behavior, the economic lens can just teach you so much like earlier

00:51:07.580 --> 00:51:12.020
[Amit Varma]: Rajeshwari you and I were at lunch and I asked a companion to ask me any question about anything

00:51:12.020 --> 00:51:16.140
[Amit Varma]: and I'll give an answer using economics and it's a one word answer. And you know, and

00:51:16.140 --> 00:51:21.940
[Amit Varma]: you can because the economic way of thinking just illuminates the whole world. Now taking

00:51:21.940 --> 00:51:26.420
[Amit Varma]: that forward, when I think of, you know, the person who asked the question that what have

00:51:26.420 --> 00:51:30.780
[Amit Varma]: you actually achieved? Now there are three ways of defining achieved, right? One is a

00:51:30.780 --> 00:51:35.580
[Amit Varma]: top down thing where a government does something. Are you influencing policy at this point in

00:51:35.580 --> 00:51:39.380
[Amit Varma]: time for the last few years? I don't think any serious economist has influenced policy

00:51:39.380 --> 00:51:46.540
[Amit Varma]: in any way. Obviously, it's just quacks and crackpots and useful idiots. Yeah, and that's

00:51:46.540 --> 00:51:51.060
[Amit Varma]: one way. But the point is, if you really want to bring about change, I've always said, don't

00:51:51.060 --> 00:51:56.140
[Amit Varma]: look at the supply end of the political marketplace, look at the demand and get your ideas out

00:51:56.140 --> 00:52:01.500
[Amit Varma]: there among the people, you know, in clear language, use those tools of economics, share

00:52:01.500 --> 00:52:05.620
[Amit Varma]: those tools of economics so others can also apply them to their own lives in the world

00:52:05.620 --> 00:52:10.020
[Amit Varma]: around you. And there I think within civil society, there are two ways this can happen.

00:52:10.020 --> 00:52:14.180
[Amit Varma]: One is civil society organizations which do their own work in their own research, like,

00:52:14.180 --> 00:52:17.300
[Amit Varma]: you know, Shrayana, you pointed out you went to Bhuvaneshwar, there are all these enthusiastic

00:52:17.300 --> 00:52:22.620
[Amit Varma]: mostly men who are, you know, doing all of what they're doing. But the other is just

00:52:22.620 --> 00:52:28.100
[Amit Varma]: this greater awareness among citizens of what is going wrong. And I think understanding

00:52:28.100 --> 00:52:34.980
[Amit Varma]: economics, understanding incentives, understanding scarcity, all of that has a big role to play

00:52:34.980 --> 00:52:39.180
[Amit Varma]: in that. And therefore, my question on funding is this, and I think it might have come up

00:52:39.180 --> 00:52:45.420
[Amit Varma]: in a different form in our episode also, Shrayana, is that in everything else, I find that things

00:52:45.420 --> 00:52:52.900
[Amit Varma]: like funding and support are in a sense, decentralized, and no longer so dependent on authorities or

00:52:52.900 --> 00:52:57.500
[Amit Varma]: mainstream platforms. So if I want to write a book, for example, sure, there might be

00:52:57.500 --> 00:53:01.180
[Amit Varma]: themes which are popular in the publishing world, which are chasing a formula and chasing

00:53:01.180 --> 00:53:06.380
[Amit Varma]: a trend. But I can write what the hell I want. And in the creator economy, you are no longer

00:53:06.380 --> 00:53:12.020
[Amit Varma]: dependent on gatekeepers. And you can, in fact, even crowdsource whatever funding you

00:53:12.020 --> 00:53:16.660
[Amit Varma]: might need for your work. And increasingly, you see this in more and more ways, even if

00:53:16.660 --> 00:53:20.580
[Amit Varma]: you don't call it crowdsourcing, everyone who's successful in the creator economy, you

00:53:20.580 --> 00:53:24.100
[Amit Varma]: know, whatever they earn through what they do, they can put it into what they do next,

00:53:24.100 --> 00:53:30.580
[Amit Varma]: as indeed I do. So is there then a possibility of, you know, economics escaping the circle

00:53:30.580 --> 00:53:35.940
[Amit Varma]: jerk and escaping this whole game of having to influence policy to be influential? Because

00:53:35.940 --> 00:53:39.900
[Amit Varma]: I think the greatest impact that economics can really have is that people see the world

00:53:39.900 --> 00:53:45.440
[Amit Varma]: differently. Today, people look around them and you know, the sort of economic illiteracy

00:53:45.440 --> 00:53:50.980
[Amit Varma]: and the how that affects the way they look at the world, it just makes me very pessimistic.

00:53:50.980 --> 00:53:54.460
[Amit Varma]: But I think that's where we kind of need to work harder. So just some rambling thoughts.

00:53:54.460 --> 00:54:01.020
[Guest 1]: What do you guys think? Again, it's not rambling, but I may be wrong in this. But I think what

00:54:01.020 --> 00:54:06.020
[Guest 1]: happens is that at the end of the day, let's say you want to earn your livelihood as an

00:54:06.020 --> 00:54:10.220
[Guest 1]: economist, right? You want to earn a living. Somebody has to pay you money, right? Unless

00:54:10.220 --> 00:54:14.380
[Guest 1]: you have enough money that you can just sit on it and do freelance economist. I mean,

00:54:14.380 --> 00:54:17.140
[Guest 1]: that also many people do and that's fine. But that's a very, very small percentage.

00:54:17.140 --> 00:54:20.980
[Guest 1]: So let's not go there. So if you want to earn your living as an economist, somebody has

00:54:20.980 --> 00:54:27.380
[Guest 1]: to pay you. And the question is, who's that somebody going to be? Is it very safe, a university,

00:54:27.380 --> 00:54:33.900
[Guest 1]: a corporate, a think tank, an NGO, a decentralized local level organization? There has to be

00:54:33.900 --> 00:54:38.700
[Guest 1]: somebody who pays you the money and whoever is paying you the money, it's not free lunch.

00:54:38.700 --> 00:54:43.820
[Guest 1]: That entity wants you to do some things in a certain way, right? While we say that as

00:54:43.820 --> 00:54:48.660
[Guest 1]: academics or as economists or as intellectuals, we have certain freedom, that freedom is also

00:54:48.660 --> 00:54:52.940
[Guest 1]: not unchecked, unrestricted, right? Now, this gets significantly worse when you're talking

00:54:52.940 --> 00:54:56.860
[Guest 1]: about funding agencies. Because when it comes to funding agencies, let's say I want to break

00:54:56.860 --> 00:55:01.700
[Guest 1]: free from the university system, right? I want to break free from institutions, I want

00:55:01.700 --> 00:55:05.060
[Guest 1]: to break free from think tanks, everything. And I just want to, as I said, set up my own

00:55:05.060 --> 00:55:09.220
[Guest 1]: center where I can do whatever I want, talk to the common man, explain economics in the

00:55:09.220 --> 00:55:12.420
[Guest 1]: common language, everything that I want to do. Who's going to pay me the money to do

00:55:12.420 --> 00:55:17.140
[Guest 1]: that? The funding agencies are not interested in that. Unless you are doing this in the

00:55:17.140 --> 00:55:22.060
[Guest 1]: field that they think will have policy implications, right? And therein comes the whole policy

00:55:22.060 --> 00:55:27.020
[Guest 1]: circle. That unless the government or the powers that we are interested in this field,

00:55:27.020 --> 00:55:31.100
[Guest 1]: the funding agencies have no incentive to fund that particular field, which means you're

00:55:31.100 --> 00:55:35.340
[Guest 1]: back to square one. Then you suddenly don't have the freedom to talk about X, Y, Z in

00:55:35.340 --> 00:55:38.940
[Guest 1]: economics that you actually are passionate about. But then you have to cater to what

00:55:38.940 --> 00:55:44.420
[Guest 1]: the funding agencies want you to do and what the policymakers want you to work on. So I

00:55:44.420 --> 00:55:50.660
[Guest 1]: think therein lies the conundrum that we haven't reached the level of sophistication of, I

00:55:50.660 --> 00:55:54.140
[Guest 1]: don't want to use the word GDP growth, but we haven't reached the sophistication of a

00:55:54.140 --> 00:55:58.940
[Guest 1]: certain level of income of the country where there is funding for any kind of discipline

00:55:58.940 --> 00:56:03.180
[Guest 1]: that a person wants to study and research in. And therefore, because there is a pyramidal

00:56:03.180 --> 00:56:09.340
[Guest 1]: impact, there is sort of like precious resources being allocated across a large number of disciplines,

00:56:09.340 --> 00:56:13.460
[Guest 1]: economics sort of is on the back burner. It's compared to, let's say, the hard sciences,

00:56:13.460 --> 00:56:17.300
[Guest 1]: compared to science and engineering research, which attracts a lot more funding. Economics

00:56:17.300 --> 00:56:21.180
[Guest 1]: as a social system and other social sciences are worse off, but we are still better off

00:56:21.180 --> 00:56:26.500
[Guest 1]: on that front. But even there, we sort of fall on the back burner. And then all of this

00:56:26.500 --> 00:56:30.500
[Guest 1]: jostling comes about that what is the field that you're interested in? But no, sorry,

00:56:30.500 --> 00:56:33.700
[Guest 1]: there is no funding in that. So therefore, you can't do anything in it. So it's not easy

00:56:33.700 --> 00:56:37.820
[Guest 1]: to break free from that and yet sustain a livelihood.

00:56:37.820 --> 00:56:43.540
[Guest 2]: I've been thinking about this actually a lot of late. And I think there are a couple of

00:56:43.540 --> 00:56:50.340
[Guest 2]: things that I feel, which are actually in the realm of, again, what the McKinsey consultants

00:56:50.340 --> 00:56:56.420
[Guest 2]: would like, low-hanging fruit. I think the first is, we have to think of more market

00:56:56.420 --> 00:57:02.500
[Guest 2]: clearing mechanisms of matching demand for certain research grants with those who have

00:57:02.500 --> 00:57:08.740
[Guest 2]: the resources to do it domestically. Because right now, I think we are living in a fool's

00:57:08.740 --> 00:57:14.420
[Guest 2]: paradise if we think this whole situation with the FCRA is going to. It's just too complicated.

00:57:14.420 --> 00:57:19.940
[Guest 2]: I also don't understand it enough, to be perfectly honest. It's just very messy. But I think

00:57:19.940 --> 00:57:24.020
[Guest 2]: there are enough deep pockets domestically. It's just that they're financing a lot of

00:57:24.020 --> 00:57:29.020
[Guest 2]: other kinds of work. A lot of money is going into invisible electoral bonds. It might be

00:57:29.020 --> 00:57:33.620
[Guest 2]: nice if some of that is, you know. So I think some of it, I'm looking, honestly, to the

00:57:33.620 --> 00:57:39.820
[Guest 2]: private sector. And I think I'm looking to technology platforms, VCs to say, can we think

00:57:39.820 --> 00:57:45.700
[Guest 2]: about a way a certain proportion of the CSR funding is pooled and you create some kind

00:57:45.700 --> 00:57:46.700
[Guest 2]: of a matching platform.

00:57:46.700 --> 00:57:51.860
[Guest 2]: There is no reason, Amit, which you described about the creator economy cannot be true for

00:57:51.860 --> 00:57:55.980
[Guest 2]: a lot of, and in fact, a lot of these research projects, you know what Rajeshwari described,

00:57:55.980 --> 00:58:01.580
[Guest 2]: it's not expensive. It's not like you're asking for core institutional grants sometimes. It

00:58:01.580 --> 00:58:07.340
[Guest 2]: might just be a small piece of work and there ought to be ways to just match. So I think

00:58:07.340 --> 00:58:12.580
[Guest 2]: this is an open challenge to anyone listening to us or anyone in the private sector who

00:58:12.580 --> 00:58:17.340
[Guest 2]: can create an aggregator platform. Let's try and think about creating something that does

00:58:17.340 --> 00:58:22.420
[Guest 2]: matching, right? That's one. I think the second is, there have to be, I think, some rules

00:58:22.420 --> 00:58:32.860
[Guest 2]: and norms in place to say that some part of the ICSSR, if I've got the acronym right,

00:58:32.860 --> 00:58:38.100
[Guest 2]: and each time nowadays I mention this acronym, my friends in Delhi at least all look very

00:58:38.100 --> 00:58:46.420
[Guest 2]: like the shoulders start to slump. I think there has to be some mechanism where, you

00:58:46.420 --> 00:58:51.300
[Guest 2]: know, yes, of course, one is despondent about reforms, but institutions do change and institutions

00:58:51.300 --> 00:58:55.420
[Guest 2]: have to be updated. We have to think very carefully about some of these social science

00:58:55.420 --> 00:59:00.740
[Guest 2]: research institutions. What can be changed? And we do currently have a government, you

00:59:00.740 --> 00:59:05.020
[Guest 2]: know, for good or for bad, is very big on administrative reform. There's a lot actually

00:59:05.020 --> 00:59:10.420
[Guest 2]: that can be done, which will tow any party line, which will make anyone look good. So

00:59:10.420 --> 00:59:15.540
[Guest 2]: I think we need to attack the fundamental problem, which is the way the government organises

00:59:15.540 --> 00:59:21.660
[Guest 2]: is also being a principal funder of a lot of this research. Either we say, well, part

00:59:21.660 --> 00:59:24.980
[Guest 2]: of the government should just get out of it. That's also a possibility. Or we start to

00:59:24.980 --> 00:59:31.540
[Guest 2]: think very carefully about how do we, in the current contemporary world that we live in,

00:59:31.540 --> 00:59:34.300
[Guest 2]: organise these institutions. So that's the second. And I don't think that that again

00:59:34.300 --> 00:59:40.500
[Guest 2]: is so difficult, it's possible to do. I think the third has to be, we need to think about,

00:59:40.500 --> 00:59:44.180
[Guest 2]: and this I know gets a little controversial, because this is where you start introducing

00:59:44.180 --> 00:59:50.300
[Guest 2]: distortions. But I really do think we need to think about financing ecosystems in smaller

00:59:50.300 --> 00:59:57.020
[Guest 2]: cities. There has to be some, I'm almost thinking like affirmative action for towns, where we

00:59:57.020 --> 01:00:02.780
[Guest 2]: say that funding has to go to core universities in places which are really, because if you

01:00:02.780 --> 01:00:06.180
[Guest 2]: look, I can actually show you a map right now. And I'm sure this is not going to surprise

01:00:06.180 --> 01:00:11.660
[Guest 2]: Rajeshwari or you Amit. But funding is very geographically concentrated. Everything is

01:00:11.660 --> 01:00:16.620
[Guest 2]: going. And by the way, it's not because researchers are often there now. In fact, many researchers

01:00:16.620 --> 01:00:22.340
[Guest 2]: are in all parts of the country. But it's because the accounting ability, the capacity

01:00:22.340 --> 01:00:26.780
[Guest 2]: to process the money, to do the procurement, all of that is actually sitting in the big

01:00:26.780 --> 01:00:32.420
[Guest 2]: cities, which is where money goes there. If you start to put in rules, which almost create

01:00:32.420 --> 01:00:39.700
[Guest 2]: this distortion and artificial allocation, maybe then we start to build, there were these

01:00:39.700 --> 01:00:43.460
[Guest 2]: good governance centers coming out, for example, from Madhya Pradesh, I'll give you that one

01:00:43.460 --> 01:00:49.460
[Guest 2]: example. Those organizations, they've done so much for the Lokseva Kendras and the right

01:00:49.460 --> 01:00:54.540
[Guest 2]: to time bound services in the state of Madhya Pradesh. This is also true for smaller towns

01:00:54.540 --> 01:00:59.580
[Guest 2]: in Karnataka, because they were doing governance research, but it was financed, some financing

01:00:59.580 --> 01:01:03.740
[Guest 2]: from government, along with organizations coming in to support. And it worked really

01:01:03.740 --> 01:01:07.660
[Guest 2]: well because now if you go to Madhya Pradesh, there is, I mean, for good or for bad, there

01:01:07.660 --> 01:01:13.100
[Guest 2]: is a thriving community of people who can explain the governance structures down to

01:01:13.100 --> 01:01:17.500
[Guest 2]: the bone to anyone who wants to understand, which is useful for politicians, is useful

01:01:17.500 --> 01:01:22.940
[Guest 2]: for what you were saying, citizens, knowing more about how government is organized, right?

01:01:22.940 --> 01:01:27.500
[Guest 2]: We need to put in these, there has to be some rules and norms such that the geographical

01:01:27.500 --> 01:01:33.700
[Guest 2]: concentration of the funding pipelines have to just radically change. It'll make people

01:01:33.700 --> 01:01:38.060
[Guest 2]: like me very unhappy because, you know, people like me want funding for projects that I want

01:01:38.060 --> 01:01:42.420
[Guest 2]: to do based out of Delhi, but I think it's time that people like me were a bit more frustrated

01:01:42.420 --> 01:01:46.620
[Guest 2]: and others received, I think, more of the allocations. I think that's the third. Last

01:01:46.620 --> 01:01:49.900
[Guest 2]: thing, actually, I said three things, but actually I have a fourth thing, which is,

01:01:49.900 --> 01:01:58.140
[Guest 2]: I really have been wondering a lot about if we were to measure our MPs or our MLAs on

01:01:58.140 --> 01:02:02.980
[Guest 2]: the measure of economic decision making. I mean, it's a very, again, this is something

01:02:02.980 --> 01:02:07.620
[Guest 2]: I've just been thinking about. It's very abstract. How do you start to crystallize that? It can't

01:02:07.620 --> 01:02:12.060
[Guest 2]: be growth because it's not something that they control and Rajeshwari will get angry

01:02:12.060 --> 01:02:18.180
[Guest 2]: at me if I even try and suggest that, but they have to be, is it roads? Maybe not because

01:02:18.180 --> 01:02:24.900
[Guest 2]: that's done by the central ministry. Can we think about incubating a research group within,

01:02:24.900 --> 01:02:28.780
[Guest 2]: you know, one of our larger, more prestigious think tanks? And again, this is an open challenge

01:02:28.780 --> 01:02:36.060
[Guest 2]: to anyone listening who thinks very carefully about how do we almost create this kind of

01:02:36.060 --> 01:02:42.500
[Guest 2]: evidence-based citizen-centric conversation around how well is my MLA doing when it comes

01:02:42.500 --> 01:02:48.180
[Guest 2]: to managing the local economy? How much does the MLA even control of the local economy?

01:02:48.180 --> 01:02:52.740
[Guest 2]: How much, you know, what can the MP do? Have they made speeches in parliament on, you know,

01:02:52.740 --> 01:02:58.220
[Guest 2]: the way certain economic decisions are being made? How have they supported the GST rationalization

01:02:58.220 --> 01:03:02.180
[Guest 2]: process as the government is trying to figure out how to implement it better? There have

01:03:02.180 --> 01:03:09.140
[Guest 2]: to be methods through which we can hold political officials much more accountable on the economy.

01:03:09.140 --> 01:03:12.860
[Guest 2]: I think what's happened is there was a method to try and do these citizen report cards.

01:03:12.860 --> 01:03:19.700
[Guest 2]: It's happened. Often they're very simple service delivery measures. Often we, you know, ADR

01:03:19.700 --> 01:03:23.940
[Guest 2]: has done a lot on corruption, right? Saying how many people have cases against them. But

01:03:23.940 --> 01:03:30.860
[Guest 2]: can we think very hard about supporting, and again, perhaps this will require, you know,

01:03:30.860 --> 01:03:36.340
[Guest 2]: large trusts and donor organizations or, you know, the private sector to support a very

01:03:36.340 --> 01:03:42.660
[Guest 2]: thought through conversation on measuring, firstly, the performance of a political office

01:03:42.660 --> 01:03:46.940
[Guest 2]: when it comes to at least the local rules of the economy that they do manage, because

01:03:46.940 --> 01:03:50.700
[Guest 2]: it's not like they can completely wash their hands of it. There are things that do sit

01:03:50.700 --> 01:03:55.380
[Guest 2]: in their control. And how do we sort of foster that conversation? I think, Amit, this goes

01:03:55.380 --> 01:03:59.260
[Guest 2]: back to what you were saying as well, which is that, you know, we see, for example, with

01:03:59.260 --> 01:04:05.660
[Guest 2]: the app, right? It was that conversation around corruption and holding MLAs and local officials

01:04:05.660 --> 01:04:11.500
[Guest 2]: politically accountable for corruption that fostered an entire social and political movement.

01:04:11.500 --> 01:04:16.100
[Guest 2]: Why don't we have that for lemon prices? You know, right now we're all discussing inflation.

01:04:16.100 --> 01:04:22.940
[Guest 2]: Can we think about breaking it down in simple ways, so that the ordinary public who is consuming

01:04:22.940 --> 01:04:28.140
[Guest 2]: this information can understand it, hold their local officials more accountable? Anyway,

01:04:28.140 --> 01:04:30.580
[Guest 2]: so this is just a list of four things.

01:04:30.580 --> 01:04:34.500
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, a couple of, you know, with this last point, and I'll go back to the earlier

01:04:34.500 --> 01:04:41.100
[Amit Varma]: ones, but a couple of issues that I see coming up here is, number one, our MPs can actually

01:04:41.100 --> 01:04:45.100
[Amit Varma]: do nothing, they're powerless, partly because of the anti-defection law. I've had episodes

01:04:45.100 --> 01:04:48.900
[Amit Varma]: on that with Varun Mitra and M. R. Madhavan, I'll link them from the show notes. But you

01:04:48.900 --> 01:04:54.020
[Amit Varma]: can run parliament from an Excel sheet, MPs are not allowed to go against the party line.

01:04:54.020 --> 01:04:59.620
[Amit Varma]: What the PMO decides is effectively what every BJP MP and MLA in this country is bound to.

01:04:59.620 --> 01:05:02.880
[Amit Varma]: So what do you hold them accountable for when you don't have the power? The second issue

01:05:02.880 --> 01:05:07.940
[Amit Varma]: is I'd done an episode with our mutual friend long ago, Shruti Rajgopalan, who has recorded

01:05:07.940 --> 01:05:12.180
[Amit Varma]: with both of you in different ways. And also as a question for you guys, I'll bring up

01:05:12.180 --> 01:05:17.460
[Amit Varma]: later, but which was about urban governance. And her point was that at the local level,

01:05:17.460 --> 01:05:23.980
[Amit Varma]: there is a disconnect between power and accountability. That, for example, the person who's, you know,

01:05:23.980 --> 01:05:29.660
[Amit Varma]: standing to be an MLA in Maharashtra or in Bombay, or who, you know, their vote base

01:05:29.660 --> 01:05:34.180
[Amit Varma]: is different. Nobody is looking at an urban vote bank in Maharashtra, they're looking

01:05:34.180 --> 01:05:38.620
[Amit Varma]: at all the different rural vote banks and all of that. Now, you might be worried about,

01:05:38.620 --> 01:05:42.500
[Amit Varma]: you know, why is the garbage not being picked up from outside, but the person you can vote

01:05:42.500 --> 01:05:47.380
[Amit Varma]: for does not control that. And the person who does control that is outside your control.

01:05:47.380 --> 01:05:50.780
[Amit Varma]: So there is that disconnect between power and accountability, which is also a question

01:05:50.780 --> 01:05:53.180
[Guest 2]: which greater local self-governance would of course help.

01:05:53.180 --> 01:05:57.220
[Guest 2]: But you know, Amit, on that, and there is actually work in economics and in political

01:05:57.220 --> 01:06:02.260
[Guest 2]: science coming out of the US, Latin America that shows when you start to even create noise

01:06:02.260 --> 01:06:07.820
[Guest 2]: about holding local officials accountable, it also then fosters inner party friction.

01:06:07.820 --> 01:06:12.980
[Guest 2]: Because right now what you have is one word goes because there's also not, you know, there's

01:06:12.980 --> 01:06:19.180
[Guest 2]: no incentive for an MLA or an MP now to fight that or fight against that sort of party line,

01:06:19.180 --> 01:06:22.580
[Guest 2]: because they are not necessarily being fully impacted or held to account for it. And I

01:06:22.580 --> 01:06:28.200
[Guest 2]: think I see and I, my sense is if we actually, and this is, I think this is why it's an open

01:06:28.200 --> 01:06:35.260
[Guest 2]: research question, to what extent can we hold political officials accountable? Or is it

01:06:35.260 --> 01:06:40.140
[Guest 2]: just that there is only everyone in the Ministry of Finance and the RBI who can be held accountable

01:06:40.140 --> 01:06:43.940
[Guest 2]: for what's happening in the economy? I don't think that that's true. I think there is actually

01:06:43.940 --> 01:06:48.740
[Guest 2]: different levels and levers of control that are available. And either you're just not

01:06:48.740 --> 01:06:54.820
[Guest 2]: exercising them, in which case then people need to know. And there has to be a more well

01:06:54.820 --> 01:06:59.780
[Guest 2]: thought out method to do that. Because right now we just don't have that conversation.

01:06:59.780 --> 01:07:05.340
[Guest 2]: I mean, in the US you have conversations around lobby groups, right? And we see that a lot.

01:07:05.340 --> 01:07:09.380
[Guest 2]: We just don't see that very clearly in our country. But who is, you know, where are we

01:07:09.380 --> 01:07:13.500
[Guest 2]: holding our political officials accountable on questions around the economy, if it isn't

01:07:13.500 --> 01:07:19.620
[Guest 2]: them profiteering off the economy in corruption? I mean, in a different way. And that's something

01:07:19.620 --> 01:07:24.220
[Guest 2]: I hope someone takes up. And I'm not completely sort of, you know, throwing that out just

01:07:24.220 --> 01:07:28.460
[Guest 2]: because MLAs and MPs don't have control over all decisions. I think there's a way you can

01:07:28.460 --> 01:07:33.300
[Guest 1]: do it. Sorry, go ahead. So I think accountability has become a pervasive

01:07:33.300 --> 01:07:38.100
[Guest 1]: problem now, right? I mean, I see instances, for example, I was shocked that you do something

01:07:38.100 --> 01:07:42.980
[Guest 1]: like demonetization, and you get away with it, right? And you win a large state election

01:07:42.980 --> 01:07:47.700
[Guest 1]: right after demonetization. To me, that was a shock. I mean, there was not a single protest

01:07:47.700 --> 01:07:52.860
[Guest 1]: all over the country, and it was a nationwide shock. And there was no protest. I mean, other

01:07:52.860 --> 01:07:59.020
[Guest 1]: than some small sporadic protests in Bengal, but in Bengal, there's a culture of protesting

01:07:59.020 --> 01:08:03.300
[Guest 1]: everything. But other than that, there was no protest anywhere in the country. And then

01:08:03.300 --> 01:08:08.100
[Guest 1]: you saw the election results. Then you have the second wave of the COVID pandemic. And

01:08:08.100 --> 01:08:11.780
[Guest 1]: we all lived through the horrors of it. And then you see the election results. And you

01:08:11.780 --> 01:08:18.060
[Guest 1]: think and wonder, what's the connect between holding the state, the government at any level,

01:08:18.060 --> 01:08:24.100
[Guest 1]: for what happened and who I'm going to vote for? So this, to me, has become almost a puzzle

01:08:24.100 --> 01:08:30.220
[Guest 1]: that how do you enforce accountability at any level of governance when it's become very

01:08:30.220 --> 01:08:35.020
[Guest 1]: easy for the government to win elections through bread and circus by providing rations and

01:08:35.020 --> 01:08:39.380
[Guest 1]: cheap internet, where everybody's going to vote on the basis of short term gains at the

01:08:39.380 --> 01:08:45.140
[Guest 1]: cost of long term pains. And therefore, where is the accountability for larger things like

01:08:45.140 --> 01:08:48.100
[Guest 1]: any of the economic issues you talk about? You talk about health care, you talk about

01:08:48.100 --> 01:08:51.420
[Guest 1]: education, you talk about corruption, you talk about infrastructure, things that we

01:08:51.420 --> 01:08:55.540
[Guest 1]: like to talk about. But when you go to the common man, what is he or she voting on? She's

01:08:55.540 --> 01:08:59.620
[Guest 1]: voting on do I have a cooking gas connection? Do I have water? Do I have electricity? Do

01:08:59.620 --> 01:09:03.180
[Guest 1]: I have a house? These are also important. But what it has boiled down to is that the

01:09:03.180 --> 01:09:08.860
[Guest 1]: government is using its limited resources to provide basic goods and services, as opposed

01:09:08.860 --> 01:09:13.380
[Guest 1]: to providing public goods and services, so to speak. And therefore, that accountability

01:09:13.380 --> 01:09:19.860
[Guest 1]: mechanism, I am happy because I can access clean water, clean cooking gas and a house,

01:09:19.860 --> 01:09:25.660
[Guest 1]: which for large spools of Indian population, that's very important. So am I going to hold

01:09:25.660 --> 01:09:30.140
[Guest 1]: the government accountable for rendering 86% of the cash invalid overnight? My life is

01:09:30.140 --> 01:09:34.940
[Guest 1]: miserable as it is, it's a little bit marginally miserable, but at least I have access to clean

01:09:34.940 --> 01:09:42.460
[Guest 1]: gas and clean water, etc. So I think, what is the connect of the citizen with the government?

01:09:42.460 --> 01:09:47.060
[Guest 1]: Does the average citizen even interact with the government on a regular basis? And I don't

01:09:47.060 --> 01:09:51.620
[Guest 1]: think they do. So therefore, in the minds of the citizenry, government is somebody who's

01:09:51.620 --> 01:09:56.380
[Guest 1]: providing maybe the basic goods and services, I'm happy with it. And therefore, come elections,

01:09:56.380 --> 01:10:00.940
[Guest 1]: for whatever compulsions, I'm going to vote for such and such local party member. Beyond

01:10:00.940 --> 01:10:06.180
[Guest 1]: that, they're not holding the government accountable for any of the things that we think are important.

01:10:06.180 --> 01:10:10.780
[Guest 1]: So I think there is a disconnect between that interaction between government on a day to

01:10:10.780 --> 01:10:15.620
[Guest 1]: day basis and a citizen's daily life. And it's very easy for a government to sort of

01:10:15.620 --> 01:10:19.220
[Guest 1]: win over that interaction by providing these basic goods, which is exactly what has gotten

01:10:19.220 --> 01:10:24.340
[Guest 1]: entrenched in Indian polity over the last several decades. So who do you hold accountable

01:10:24.340 --> 01:10:28.580
[Guest 1]: for what? I mean, how do you hold RBI accountable for what it's doing? How do you hold Ministry

01:10:28.580 --> 01:10:32.460
[Guest 1]: of Finance? I'm not even going at the decentralised level. At the centralised level, there's no

01:10:32.460 --> 01:10:35.980
[Guest 1]: accountability. At the decentralised level, there's no accountability. I mean, think of

01:10:35.980 --> 01:10:41.020
[Guest 1]: the Bengal elections. I know Bengal because I'm from Bengal. How do you win elections?

01:10:41.020 --> 01:10:46.540
[Guest 1]: You float a lot of schemes which are women-centric. Women come out in hordes to cast votes. That's

01:10:46.540 --> 01:10:49.780
[Guest 1]: a remarkable thing. Great. But why are the women voting? Because most of the schemes

01:10:49.780 --> 01:10:55.620
[Guest 1]: are directed towards women. Is there any emphasis on job creation? Is there any emphasis on

01:10:55.620 --> 01:10:59.300
[Guest 1]: actually building infrastructure assets or anything that's going to promote long term

01:10:59.300 --> 01:11:04.020
[Guest 1]: sustainable job creation and growth? No. So it's become increasingly easy for political

01:11:04.020 --> 01:11:09.300
[Guest 1]: parties to win elections, which is what they most care about. And in that kind of a system

01:11:09.300 --> 01:11:14.460
[Guest 1]: where you can just win elections by providing freebies and basic goods, how do you hold

01:11:14.460 --> 01:11:21.180
[Guest 2]: anybody accountable? Where is the accountability? I hear what Rajeshwari is saying. I disagree

01:11:21.180 --> 01:11:27.300
[Guest 2]: with the, now this is my Bengali lefty self, the little bit of the Bengali in me. I'm kidding.

01:11:27.300 --> 01:11:32.740
[Guest 2]: But I disagree with, they're not freebies because we do live in a world, particularly

01:11:32.740 --> 01:11:37.700
[Guest 2]: coming out of the pandemic, where most of the country is between the poverty line and

01:11:37.700 --> 01:11:43.980
[Guest 2]: twice the poverty line. I mean, this is a, we are, it's a really dire situation. Extreme

01:11:43.980 --> 01:11:49.140
[Guest 2]: poverty has reduced in India, continues to reduce, but precarity has just increased incredible

01:11:49.140 --> 01:11:55.220
[Guest 2]: levels. We know from RCTs across the globe and also work that's happening in India that

01:11:55.220 --> 01:11:59.080
[Guest 2]: you need some assurance and these transfers are very important. I think what needs to

01:11:59.080 --> 01:12:03.580
[Guest 2]: happen and I know maybe we'll come to this later. I think one of the core reforms that

01:12:03.580 --> 01:12:09.420
[Guest 2]: certainly something in my work I'm really pushing is India needs to have a social protection

01:12:09.420 --> 01:12:13.380
[Guest 2]: policy. What other countries would call a social protection policy. I think it links

01:12:13.380 --> 01:12:17.900
[Guest 2]: to what Rajeshwari is saying, which is you need to have a fiscal path on which these

01:12:17.900 --> 01:12:22.380
[Guest 2]: kinds of entitlements and programs operate. So if you look at, you know, Brazil or Mexico

01:12:22.380 --> 01:12:27.860
[Guest 2]: and many of these countries, you essentially have a very clear policy path, which says

01:12:27.860 --> 01:12:32.260
[Guest 2]: certain X share on spending, there are limits and rules, there are rules of the game. I

01:12:32.260 --> 01:12:36.900
[Guest 2]: think what's happened here is you have 20 pension schemes, they're targeting the same

01:12:36.900 --> 01:12:40.060
[Guest 2]: person and often the person who's supposed to get it doesn't get it, right? There are

01:12:40.060 --> 01:12:44.980
[Guest 2]: all these issues. I think there has to be a way and first you need to bind different

01:12:44.980 --> 01:12:49.940
[Guest 2]: groups of government into a policy framework. Right now, we don't think about it like that.

01:12:49.940 --> 01:12:53.820
[Guest 2]: I think some states are thinking about it like that. And I am hoping, you know, in the

01:12:53.820 --> 01:12:57.540
[Guest 2]: future that this is something that the national government at least will have to think about

01:12:57.540 --> 01:13:02.220
[Guest 2]: because it's also fiscally unsustainable beyond a path. Having said that, I think I agree

01:13:02.220 --> 01:13:09.940
[Guest 2]: with everything Rajeshwari just said. But what I will say is, I mean, jobs, for example,

01:13:09.940 --> 01:13:14.820
[Guest 2]: it's just fascinating to me, jobs and inflation, actually. And I'm curious to hear what Rajeshwari

01:13:14.820 --> 01:13:20.340
[Guest 2]: and you Amit have to say. I don't know, coming out of the UP election, I think all of us

01:13:20.340 --> 01:13:26.100
[Guest 2]: had this moment of tremendous, I don't know, I don't even call it pause. I think it was

01:13:26.100 --> 01:13:33.060
[Guest 2]: just somewhat, because is it the case that jobs just don't matter anymore? I was seeing

01:13:33.060 --> 01:13:38.260
[Guest 2]: some really interesting journalists reporting out of UP essentially saying, similar to what

01:13:38.260 --> 01:13:43.620
[Guest 2]: I think Rajeshwari is saying, which is that as long as you have a core set of entitlements,

01:13:43.620 --> 01:13:47.460
[Guest 2]: but it's interesting because I also know the data and UP to know that the people who actually

01:13:47.460 --> 01:13:52.820
[Guest 2]: are targeted for, I mean, who should be receiving priority for those entitlements don't get

01:13:52.820 --> 01:13:58.620
[Guest 2]: the full basket. Is it that jobs just don't politically matter? I think that's an open

01:13:58.620 --> 01:14:03.060
[Guest 2]: question and honestly, it's something that I don't have an answer to. I know that women's

01:14:03.060 --> 01:14:09.740
[Guest 2]: jobs don't matter at all. I don't think anyone cares. I think we are very happy with equilibrium

01:14:09.740 --> 01:14:14.220
[Guest 2]: in the employment landscape when it comes to women. But I'm wondering whether jobs just

01:14:14.220 --> 01:14:18.540
[Guest 2]: have stopped mattering as a political issue. I mean, did they matter in the history of

01:14:18.540 --> 01:14:23.260
[Guest 2]: our country's economy? I wonder, I mean, this is a question for us to think about. And the

01:14:23.260 --> 01:14:28.340
[Guest 2]: same for inflation. I mean, look at what's happening right now. Now, in fact, I do see,

01:14:28.340 --> 01:14:33.500
[Guest 2]: of course, the opposition has picked up on it. But I wonder that, and I don't know if

01:14:33.500 --> 01:14:38.180
[Guest 2]: it's just, honestly, Rajeshwari, I don't know whether it's just that you've been sedated

01:14:38.180 --> 01:14:43.260
[Guest 2]: as an electorate through welfare, because actually not everyone is receiving the welfare

01:14:43.260 --> 01:14:47.740
[Guest 2]: transfers. I mean, it's not also, we saw what happened with migrants going back during the

01:14:47.740 --> 01:14:52.940
[Guest 2]: crisis. The One Nation One Ration card is yet to fully take off. It's not the case that

01:14:52.940 --> 01:14:56.460
[Guest 2]: everybody's receiving the entitlements. In fact, you have activists arguing for deeper

01:14:56.460 --> 01:15:01.560
[Guest 2]: entitlements because there are concerns about some people just being completely left out.

01:15:01.560 --> 01:15:05.960
[Guest 2]: So I wonder what's going on. I mean, what are you, I mean, if jobs and inflation are

01:15:05.960 --> 01:15:11.940
[Guest 2]: not political issues anymore, which all of us in our one training were told that, well,

01:15:11.940 --> 01:15:17.540
[Guest 2]: they are, they should be. I wonder what is the labour market now? Is the labour market

01:15:17.540 --> 01:15:22.100
[Guest 2]: basically getting paid to, I don't know, harass people online? I mean, are those the jobs

01:15:22.100 --> 01:15:26.300
[Guest 2]: that we are going to create? I wonder, is that now what the job market is? It's an open

01:15:26.300 --> 01:15:27.300
[Guest 1]: question to both of you.

01:15:27.300 --> 01:15:32.300
[Guest 1]: So I have several points to make, Amit, if I can. So one is that I do agree that the

01:15:32.300 --> 01:15:37.160
[Guest 1]: pandemic was obviously, it's an outlier rare event, right? And when a rare event like this

01:15:37.160 --> 01:15:43.100
[Guest 1]: hits a country, you need to do redistribution because the situation is absolutely dire.

01:15:43.100 --> 01:15:48.820
[Guest 1]: But I think there is a case to be made that redistribution should focus more on rare events

01:15:48.820 --> 01:15:54.780
[Guest 1]: rather than become a norm. And I think what we have internalised is we have a redistributive

01:15:54.780 --> 01:15:59.860
[Guest 1]: model of development. And that is what we have internalised over the decades. And that

01:15:59.860 --> 01:16:05.700
[Guest 1]: is what gets used in election cycle to basically win the elections. And that's where the accountability

01:16:05.700 --> 01:16:08.980
[Guest 1]: breaks down, right? So basically, I guess what I'm trying to say is that if the common

01:16:08.980 --> 01:16:13.700
[Guest 1]: voter is happy with the basic goods that are being provided, irrespective of a pandemic,

01:16:13.700 --> 01:16:17.620
[Guest 1]: then what is the incentive of that common voter to say that, no, I'm going to hold you

01:16:17.620 --> 01:16:21.660
[Guest 1]: accountable for all these other problems that's happening in my locality, right? I think that

01:16:21.660 --> 01:16:26.860
[Guest 1]: incentive structure is very weak. And that is something that has somehow smoothly happened.

01:16:26.860 --> 01:16:30.660
[Guest 1]: If there's one thing that has smoothly happened in India over the decades, it is this idea

01:16:30.660 --> 01:16:37.100
[Guest 1]: that you can give the common man these basic goods and services and he or she is okay with

01:16:37.100 --> 01:16:41.900
[Guest 1]: it because you're starting from such a low level, but you provide that and they need

01:16:41.900 --> 01:16:46.340
[Guest 1]: that basic standard of life and the government is providing that. And then they no longer

01:16:46.340 --> 01:16:49.900
[Guest 1]: feel the necessity to hold the government accountable for all the things that we think

01:16:49.900 --> 01:16:55.980
[Guest 1]: are important in the long run, right? And the second thing is, I think jobs were never

01:16:55.980 --> 01:17:01.100
[Guest 1]: really that important when it came to winning elections, right? Because India traditionally

01:17:01.100 --> 01:17:05.940
[Guest 1]: has had a very high unemployment rate or a very low employment rate, because I don't

01:17:05.940 --> 01:17:10.140
[Guest 1]: particularly trust the official unemployment numbers. But if I just look at CMI's, Labour

01:17:10.140 --> 01:17:14.580
[Guest 1]: Force Participation Rate, right, we've always had a very miserable statistic as far as jobs

01:17:14.580 --> 01:17:19.100
[Guest 1]: is concerned. So any incremental improvement on that almost feels like something great

01:17:19.100 --> 01:17:24.300
[Guest 1]: has happened. And I completely agree that women's abysmally low LFPR just does not matter

01:17:24.300 --> 01:17:31.020
[Guest 1]: to anybody. That's not even an electoral agenda. But basically, the fact that jobs have never

01:17:31.020 --> 01:17:36.260
[Guest 1]: really been a decision making point when it comes to winning elections says a lot about

01:17:36.260 --> 01:17:40.980
[Guest 1]: what is it that the people of India really care about, right? And that's where I think,

01:17:40.980 --> 01:17:47.220
[Guest 1]: if you're getting the welfare entitlements, and you're okay, and you're not holding the

01:17:47.220 --> 01:17:52.480
[Guest 1]: government responsible for not having jobs. So I think the accountability is not directly

01:17:52.480 --> 01:17:58.100
[Guest 1]: being lined with the government not providing jobs. But I think what does matter is inflation.

01:17:58.100 --> 01:18:05.340
[Guest 1]: In fact, 2014 election was lost on two counts, I think one was corruption, and one was inflation,

01:18:05.340 --> 01:18:10.420
[Guest 1]: because prices were exorbitantly high. And inflation is like the tax on the poor people,

01:18:10.420 --> 01:18:14.940
[Guest 1]: right? And it's the worst tax on the poor people. So when you have uncontrollable inflation

01:18:14.940 --> 01:18:21.060
[Guest 1]: that you're just not able to manage, I think that definitely becomes a very deep political

01:18:21.060 --> 01:18:26.080
[Guest 1]: problem. And that's what I would be very curious to see what happens in 2024. Because we definitely

01:18:26.080 --> 01:18:30.820
[Guest 1]: have lost control on inflation, the way things are looking like. So I think jobs is something

01:18:30.820 --> 01:18:36.460
[Guest 1]: that the voter perhaps does not worry about as much when it comes to voting, but inflation

01:18:36.460 --> 01:18:40.420
[Guest 1]: definitely something and corruption. I think one of the reasons the government got away

01:18:40.420 --> 01:18:45.220
[Guest 1]: with demonetization was that the selling point was this is an anti-corruption measure. And

01:18:45.220 --> 01:18:49.940
[Guest 1]: they feel so the average person feels so strongly about corruption, that it was easy to even

01:18:49.940 --> 01:18:54.140
[Guest 1]: get away with something like demonetization. But I think inflation will be much harder

01:18:54.140 --> 01:18:59.660
[Guest 1]: to get away with and something has to be done soon. But yeah, I constantly worry about accountability.

01:18:59.660 --> 01:19:05.500
[Guest 1]: I mean, in a democracy, our only weapon of holding the government accountable is elections.

01:19:05.500 --> 01:19:10.820
[Guest 1]: And if that's where this whole connect has broken down, how do you hold anybody accountable?

01:19:10.820 --> 01:19:14.580
[Amit Varma]: I think I'll double down on what you just said and what you said earlier, because that

01:19:14.580 --> 01:19:19.020
[Amit Varma]: was actually the third doubt I had about your point of making politicians more accountable

01:19:19.020 --> 01:19:25.060
[Amit Varma]: through good economics. Because my cynical take there is that ultimately, you hold people

01:19:25.060 --> 01:19:29.580
[Amit Varma]: accountable on the basis of what you believe about them. And it comes down to narratives,

01:19:29.580 --> 01:19:34.300
[Amit Varma]: not facts. And often good economic narratives are much harder to sell. For example, I think

01:19:34.300 --> 01:19:38.620
[Amit Varma]: we'd all agree that you should allow every eye in retail, because it's good for people

01:19:38.620 --> 01:19:43.420
[Amit Varma]: at large, and so on and so forth. I mean, hardly needs to be stated. But it's very easy

01:19:43.420 --> 01:19:48.700
[Amit Varma]: for a politician to oppose it by saying what about the small traders, what will happen

01:19:48.700 --> 01:19:52.100
[Amit Varma]: to their livelihoods, you know, look at the scene effects and not the unseen effects around

01:19:52.100 --> 01:19:57.260
[Amit Varma]: the line, so on and so forth. And those narrative battles are ones which are hard to win.

01:19:57.260 --> 01:20:03.020
[Guest 1]: I'll give you another big example, Amit. For the longest of time, we were fighting with

01:20:03.020 --> 01:20:08.700
[Guest 1]: this FRDI bill, which is resolution of financial firms, right. And it's a very, very important

01:20:08.700 --> 01:20:13.580
[Guest 1]: policy step to take. Because while we have a bankruptcy procedure, when non financial

01:20:13.580 --> 01:20:18.460
[Guest 1]: firms go bankrupt, and how do you just resolve them, there is absolutely nothing for financial

01:20:18.460 --> 01:20:23.340
[Guest 1]: firms, for banks, etc. Of course, it's a different matter in India, banks never fail. But that's

01:20:23.340 --> 01:20:27.500
[Guest 1]: that doesn't mean that they are healthy. I mean, it's just like a, you know, facade

01:20:27.500 --> 01:20:32.460
[Guest 1]: that that we are all very comfortable with. But then how do you deal with failed financial

01:20:32.460 --> 01:20:38.460
[Guest 1]: firms, and there was a bill that was almost tabled, and a lot of people we know, they

01:20:38.460 --> 01:20:43.420
[Guest 1]: worked on the bill, but then the FRDI bill got completely shelved, because the narrative

01:20:43.420 --> 01:20:47.260
[Guest 1]: got spun in a very different way that the common man is going to lose bank deposits,

01:20:47.260 --> 01:20:51.420
[Guest 1]: the common man is going to get the raw deal, because there is no insurance against deposits,

01:20:51.420 --> 01:20:55.260
[Guest 1]: and what's going to happen. And immediately, the whole political narrative changed, and

01:20:55.260 --> 01:20:59.900
[Guest 1]: you lost the popular support, and the bill got shelved. But I guess that therein lies

01:20:59.900 --> 01:21:05.020
[Guest 1]: the importance of the powers that be to realize what is important for the economy in the long

01:21:05.020 --> 01:21:08.940
[Guest 1]: run, or for the country for the long run as a strategy, as opposed to just selling something

01:21:08.940 --> 01:21:12.300
[Amit Varma]: that will be very popular for the voters. But you know, that's again, never going to

01:21:12.300 --> 01:21:15.820
[Amit Varma]: happen. Because you know, public choice theory would tell you the politician is focused on

01:21:15.820 --> 01:21:18.380
[Amit Varma]: the next elections. And that's our constant conundrum.

01:21:18.380 --> 01:21:21.980
[Guest 2]: But you know, but here's the thing. So, you know, just a couple of things. So let's

01:21:21.980 --> 01:21:25.020
[Guest 2]: take Chhattisgarh, as I'm just going to keep going back to Chhattisgarh for some reason.

01:21:25.820 --> 01:21:29.580
[Guest 2]: Chhattisgarh was one of the first states after Tamil Nadu to say, well, we'll universalize

01:21:29.580 --> 01:21:35.340
[Guest 2]: the food ration program, right? And you did have that particular Mr. Raman Singh's government,

01:21:35.340 --> 01:21:40.540
[Guest 2]: they came back to power a few times, but eventually they lost as well. And it's not for

01:21:40.540 --> 01:21:44.700
[Guest 2]: the welfare transfers were working well. There are many states, in fact, where they've

01:21:44.700 --> 01:21:52.140
[Guest 2]: universalized the welfare programs, a core set, and yet you've had churn. And so clearly

01:21:52.140 --> 01:21:58.220
[Guest 2]: there is, you know, I want us to sort of think a bit more critically, because I think it's

01:21:58.220 --> 01:22:02.860
[Guest 2]: become now, I hear this amongst a lot of economists, which is well, you know, it's sort of,

01:22:02.860 --> 01:22:06.940
[Guest 2]: it's just welfare for votes or handouts, right? It's just another word I don't like.

01:22:08.300 --> 01:22:12.540
[Guest 2]: I think there's something deeper going on. I think what's happening is,

01:22:12.540 --> 01:22:18.460
[Guest 2]: it's also in relation to what's happening to other markets, because if you have a job

01:22:18.460 --> 01:22:23.100
[Guest 2]: market, that's always been precarious. I think part of the reason why jobs have never really

01:22:23.100 --> 01:22:26.860
[Guest 2]: been a political agenda, and this is going back to, you know, you have a largely informal

01:22:26.860 --> 01:22:32.140
[Guest 2]: economy, jobs are extremely ad hoc, they are human arrangements, right? What are jobs?

01:22:32.140 --> 01:22:37.500
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's a set of relationships. And in that world where there's always flux,

01:22:37.500 --> 01:22:41.500
[Guest 2]: I'm not surprised that people think that, well, you know, politicians can necessarily

01:22:41.500 --> 01:22:47.260
[Guest 2]: not intervene. However, what did happen was there was NREGA. And when NREGA did happen,

01:22:47.260 --> 01:22:51.500
[Guest 2]: it has completely, I mean, there are studies that show really rigorous work that shows

01:22:51.500 --> 01:22:56.860
[Guest 2]: it has radically transformed the, you know, the reservation wage for someone involved

01:22:56.860 --> 01:23:03.420
[Guest 2]: in the rural economy. And that's really important intervention. Now, I don't see again in politics,

01:23:03.420 --> 01:23:08.060
[Guest 2]: people necessarily, perhaps after a certain point, holding any politician accountable

01:23:08.060 --> 01:23:12.780
[Guest 2]: for how well NREGA is functioning in a particular state. And in some states NREGA ought to function

01:23:12.780 --> 01:23:18.380
[Guest 2]: because agrarian job markets and labor markets are really breaking down. And you would think

01:23:18.380 --> 01:23:23.260
[Guest 2]: in that context, and especially in inflationary context as well, NREGA is self-selection,

01:23:23.260 --> 01:23:27.420
[Guest 2]: you're supposed to demand that work. And it is a job market intervention. I mean, it's

01:23:27.420 --> 01:23:33.420
[Guest 2]: not just a welfare scheme, it's actually trying to attack the labor market. And yet I don't

01:23:33.420 --> 01:23:39.900
[Guest 2]: see, it's not necessarily yet as politicized a scheme as at a point of time it used to

01:23:39.900 --> 01:23:45.260
[Guest 2]: be, right? And I wonder, and I don't have an answer for this. I mean, these are just

01:23:45.260 --> 01:23:49.100
[Guest 2]: questions I have, I wonder what's going on. Maybe I think if I may just interrupt, maybe

01:23:49.100 --> 01:23:53.100
[Guest 1]: because the NREGA was, I mean, and I agree, it's a brilliant scheme. And I think we should

01:23:53.100 --> 01:23:57.340
[Guest 1]: have an urban NREGA as well after what happened in the pandemic. But I think it's because

01:23:57.340 --> 01:24:02.460
[Guest 1]: NREGA was essentially a brainchild of the previous government. And maybe that's the

01:24:02.460 --> 01:24:07.820
[Guest 1]: government. And maybe that's why we don't see NREGA come repeatedly and showcased as,

01:24:07.820 --> 01:24:11.660
[Guest 1]: because it is a successful strategy. And in fact, it was a savior during the pandemic.

01:24:11.660 --> 01:24:14.860
[Guest 1]: But what we saw in the budget is that the government has actually reduced the allocation

01:24:14.860 --> 01:24:19.660
[Guest 1]: on NREGA. And maybe that would not have happened if it was their brainchild. But I'm just brainstorming

01:24:19.660 --> 01:24:20.660
[Guest 2]: at this point of time.

01:24:20.660 --> 01:24:23.660
[Guest 2]: Yeah, but I think Rajeshwari, actually, I do have to say, I think when it comes to welfare,

01:24:23.660 --> 01:24:29.260
[Guest 2]: there's tremendous continuity across political lines. In fact, that's one thing that's very

01:24:29.260 --> 01:24:34.700
[Guest 2]: interesting about the Indian polity. And I know that that bothers some who think about

01:24:34.700 --> 01:24:38.060
[Guest 2]: it as sort of, well, again, you know, as you were saying, like this sort of distorts clear

01:24:38.060 --> 01:24:43.340
[Guest 2]: accountability mechanisms, distorts other markets as well, right? But what's interesting

01:24:43.340 --> 01:24:47.420
[Guest 2]: to me, for example, is NREGA actually for the previous budgets, the allocations actually

01:24:47.420 --> 01:24:53.500
[Guest 2]: increased under a different political dispensation. In fact, this government has used the National

01:24:53.500 --> 01:24:59.420
[Guest 2]: Food Security Act to even open up further. So I almost see this deepening. I think what's

01:24:59.420 --> 01:25:05.260
[Guest 2]: happening, though, is that while the welfare story is sort of, you know, moving along a

01:25:05.260 --> 01:25:11.500
[Guest 2]: certain path, I think the question really is, we now have a welfare system, which is

01:25:11.500 --> 01:25:17.660
[Guest 2]: very broad, in that there are lots of schemes. Currently, there are around 464 national programs.

01:25:18.220 --> 01:25:21.900
[Guest 2]: States have their own, a state like Kerala even has programs at the panchayat level.

01:25:21.900 --> 01:25:25.900
[Guest 2]: And yet the depth is very limited. So the actual amount that people are receiving is

01:25:25.900 --> 01:25:32.380
[Guest 2]: very small. And I suspect actually, the reason why you almost have this rewarding of schemes

01:25:32.380 --> 01:25:37.900
[Guest 2]: is precisely because you don't have one large lump sum transfer. My sense is that if we

01:25:37.900 --> 01:25:43.020
[Guest 2]: actually thought very cohesively in a way about welfare, it would actually be beneficial

01:25:43.020 --> 01:25:46.860
[Guest 2]: for politicians as well, because you could say, well, this is a national transfer. Maybe

01:25:46.860 --> 01:25:51.260
[Guest 2]: the state government does a top up NREGA and PDS function. And then let's think about

01:25:51.260 --> 01:25:57.580
[Guest 2]: consolidating all these other legacy programs. But I just don't, again, and this is

01:25:57.580 --> 01:26:02.780
[Guest 2]: something that is good politics, it would be good economics. But I just don't see again,

01:26:02.780 --> 01:26:08.300
[Guest 2]: the energy to sort of move in that direction. Perhaps we'll see it. There is an election

01:26:08.300 --> 01:26:13.980
[Guest 2]: coming up soon. Maybe we'll see it. But I think to just go back to, I agree with what

01:26:13.980 --> 01:26:18.860
[Guest 2]: you said, Rajeshwari, but I also wonder, you know, I think the reason why welfare keeps

01:26:18.860 --> 01:26:23.660
[Guest 2]: coming up to be this important electoral almost issue is because actually, the benefits

01:26:23.660 --> 01:26:27.900
[Guest 2]: are so small, and you're not even guaranteed if you work on NREGA. We know studies show

01:26:27.900 --> 01:26:32.220
[Guest 2]: you don't even know when you will get your wages. There are wage backlogs for a very

01:26:32.220 --> 01:26:37.180
[Guest 2]: long period of time. And so I think, you know, there is this, so it's almost transactional

01:26:37.180 --> 01:26:41.900
[Guest 2]: because the actual depth of the benefits and what people are receiving is so unsure and

01:26:41.900 --> 01:26:45.420
[Guest 2]: insecure. So I think, Amit, going back to the question, I think the idea of holding

01:26:45.420 --> 01:26:49.980
[Guest 2]: a local politician accountable for good economic choices, it's not just sort of, you know,

01:26:49.980 --> 01:26:54.380
[Guest 2]: what can you do on broad budget, broad bills and budget bills, and so on and so forth.

01:26:54.380 --> 01:26:58.540
[Guest 2]: I think it's also the local economy, because there are roles. And again, this is a research

01:26:58.540 --> 01:27:03.580
[Guest 2]: question. What are the roles and levers that a local politician has to impact the local

01:27:03.580 --> 01:27:08.140
[Guest 2]: labour market? I'm thinking of NREGA as one of them, because they do exert tremendous

01:27:08.140 --> 01:27:13.900
[Guest 2]: influence on the way panchayats are able to administer or push them to administer certain

01:27:13.900 --> 01:27:19.260
[Guest 2]: programs. I wonder if there are others as well. I suspect PM Kisan is one of them, just

01:27:19.260 --> 01:27:24.780
[Guest 2]: as an example. It's the quasi basic income for certain groups of farmers. And I think

01:27:24.780 --> 01:27:29.340
[Guest 2]: that's where I think we should think a bit more carefully. But how do we start to at

01:27:29.340 --> 01:27:35.020
[Guest 2]: least generate more evidence, which I realised then goes back to that circle of when we need

01:27:35.020 --> 01:27:39.260
[Guest 2]: to raise resources for that kind of work. But I think that's, I feel like that's really

01:27:39.260 --> 01:27:41.820
[Guest 2]: where maybe we're not talking about what economists are doing, but what economists

01:27:41.820 --> 01:27:44.300
[Guest 2]: now ought to be thinking about and doing. So let's see.

01:27:45.180 --> 01:27:48.460
[Amit Varma]: I mean, as an aside, I would say that just going back to the resources question, I think

01:27:48.460 --> 01:27:53.340
[Amit Varma]: there are new ways of thinking about it, which will become more and more popular, like what

01:27:53.340 --> 01:27:57.900
[Amit Varma]: Shruti does with Emergent Ventures, for example, where you just give money to someone and then

01:27:57.900 --> 01:28:02.060
[Amit Varma]: you don't ask any questions, you just give it to them. And I really like that model where

01:28:02.060 --> 01:28:07.180
[Amit Varma]: you identify the people you trust, who you feel will do interesting work, and then you

01:28:07.180 --> 01:28:11.020
[Amit Varma]: don't ask any more questions after that. You trust those people to do whatever it is they

01:28:11.020 --> 01:28:16.540
[Amit Varma]: do that works. I think that deeper kinds of crowdsourcing can also work over time, it

01:28:16.540 --> 01:28:22.620
[Amit Varma]: just doesn't have to be either the government or institutions or even, you know, private

01:28:22.620 --> 01:28:28.220
[Amit Varma]: companies deciding to do this, I think it can also come from a different place. And

01:28:29.020 --> 01:28:33.580
[Amit Varma]: as far as people, you know, not voting with where the interest should lie, I would say

01:28:33.580 --> 01:28:38.780
[Amit Varma]: a lot of that is also apathy. Like there's this beautiful saying from Kashi Kasi, which

01:28:38.780 --> 01:28:41.580
[Amit Varma]: has almost become a cliche on the show, because I love it so much. I keep saying it.

01:28:41.580 --> 01:28:42.540
[Guest 1]: The harmonia one.

01:28:42.540 --> 01:28:47.020
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. Bhaar mein jaye duniya, hum bhajaye harmonia. I think that's everyone's attitude,

01:28:47.020 --> 01:28:51.260
[Amit Varma]: man, because nobody expects anything from any government after 70 something years of

01:28:51.260 --> 01:28:56.940
[Amit Varma]: misgovernance, basically. Now, I want to focus on a different question and go on a rant that

01:28:56.940 --> 01:29:02.540
[Amit Varma]: might seem unrelated, but in a sense is unrelated. A couple of people on Twitter, you know, where

01:29:02.540 --> 01:29:09.260
[Amit Varma]: we solicited questions, spoke about inequality, right? And, you know, I had written a column,

01:29:09.260 --> 01:29:14.140
[Amit Varma]: which I linked from the show notes pointing out that, listen, inequality is a Western obsession.

01:29:15.420 --> 01:29:19.820
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's a luxury of the elites, we need to focus on poverty, poverty and inequality

01:29:19.820 --> 01:29:24.940
[Amit Varma]: are completely different things. And the reason people conflate the two is really zero-sum

01:29:24.940 --> 01:29:29.820
[Amit Varma]: thinking, which is something pervasive that economists have to fight all the time, that,

01:29:29.820 --> 01:29:33.980
[Amit Varma]: you know, if somebody is getting poorer, somebody must be getting richer, and therefore inequality

01:29:33.980 --> 01:29:39.500
[Amit Varma]: and poverty, they go together. Now, that's not the case. Inequality and poverty often go in

01:29:39.500 --> 01:29:43.740
[Amit Varma]: opposite directions. Like one thought experiment question I like to ask people is, in which of

01:29:43.740 --> 01:29:49.100
[Amit Varma]: these two countries would you rather be poor, Bangladesh or the USA? And obviously, you'd

01:29:49.100 --> 01:29:54.940
[Amit Varma]: rather be poor in the USA and the USA has far more inequality than Bangladesh does. In fact,

01:29:54.940 --> 01:30:00.140
[Amit Varma]: countries like USA, Hong Kong, Singapore, the United Kingdom have greater inequality than Bangladesh,

01:30:00.140 --> 01:30:05.180
[Amit Varma]: Liberia, Pakistan and Sierra Leone. But these last four countries I name have greater poverty,

01:30:05.180 --> 01:30:09.180
[Amit Varma]: right? Now, what has happened after liberalization is we've lifted hundreds of millions of people

01:30:09.180 --> 01:30:14.700
[Amit Varma]: out of poverty as inequality has increased. This is counterintuitive, because you would imagine that,

01:30:14.700 --> 01:30:18.940
[Amit Varma]: you know, poverty and inequality go hand in hand. Now, I find that when many people when they talk

01:30:18.940 --> 01:30:23.020
[Amit Varma]: about inequality, they actually mean poverty, they're thinking of the plight of poor people.

01:30:23.020 --> 01:30:28.620
[Amit Varma]: But that's a different thing. And I think language kind of matters. Inequality per se,

01:30:28.620 --> 01:30:32.780
[Amit Varma]: need not necessarily be a problem. I think it's a big problem in another domain, which I'll ask

01:30:32.780 --> 01:30:37.980
[Amit Varma]: you about Rajeshwari later, because you're a macro economist, and therefore the perfect person

01:30:37.980 --> 01:30:43.980
[Amit Varma]: for that. Now, and you know, another illustration of why inequality is not a big deal poverty is,

01:30:43.980 --> 01:30:48.540
[Amit Varma]: is throughout history, people have moved from towns to cities, villages to towns,

01:30:48.540 --> 01:30:53.660
[Amit Varma]: they are moving to towards a place of greater inequality, because what matters is escaping

01:30:53.660 --> 01:30:59.020
[Amit Varma]: poverty. And the reason I say this is that the solutions for both are often opposite,

01:30:59.020 --> 01:31:03.580
[Amit Varma]: right? And I think that there is a trade off between redistribution and growth. I think what

01:31:03.580 --> 01:31:09.660
[Amit Varma]: you really need to do is and I agree with you that in a desperately poor country, where some 8000

01:31:09.660 --> 01:31:14.780
[Amit Varma]: children die every day of starvation, you need certain kinds of welfare policies to alleviate

01:31:14.780 --> 01:31:19.420
[Amit Varma]: that and NREGA is a great thing. However, I would like to live in an India where NREGA is not

01:31:19.420 --> 01:31:24.940
[Amit Varma]: necessary, where you know, the rising tide has lifted all boats where we have greater economic

01:31:24.940 --> 01:31:30.860
[Amit Varma]: growth. So I just want to kind of conceptually be sort of clear about this like I go by like

01:31:30.860 --> 01:31:35.180
[Amit Varma]: Harry Frankfurt wrote a book called on inequality where he came up with this concept I love, which

01:31:35.180 --> 01:31:41.100
[Amit Varma]: is a doctrine of sufficiency. And that guides my thinking that my thinking is guided by does

01:31:41.100 --> 01:31:46.540
[Amit Varma]: every person have enough to live a life of sufficiency, which you can define any way you

01:31:46.540 --> 01:31:49.980
[Amit Varma]: want, right? And I won't have a problem with whatever definition you come up with. But the

01:31:49.980 --> 01:31:54.860
[Amit Varma]: idea is let's take everybody there, let's get out of poverty. And therefore, I find that there is

01:31:54.860 --> 01:31:59.900
[Amit Varma]: this sort of, you know, when we conflate these two, and when you know, when we use inequality,

01:31:59.900 --> 01:32:05.260
[Amit Varma]: when we mean poverty, and when we come up with policies that might help inequality by making

01:32:05.260 --> 01:32:11.500
[Amit Varma]: everybody equally poor, you know, that becomes an issue. So when we talk of welfare and redistribution,

01:32:11.500 --> 01:32:16.460
[Amit Varma]: I get it at one level, but I also feel disturbed at another level. Because the point is, for

01:32:16.460 --> 01:32:20.860
[Amit Varma]: example, has become the regal now for all politicians in every election to say to the

01:32:20.860 --> 01:32:26.620
[Amit Varma]: people farm loan waivers. Now, farm loan waivers to me might be a necessary anesthetic at a moment

01:32:26.620 --> 01:32:32.300
[Amit Varma]: in time. But you are shifting the focus from the larger greater structural problems you need to

01:32:32.300 --> 01:32:38.700
[Guest 2]: resolve. I don't even think that a farm waiver is welfare policy. Because if you mean there are

01:32:38.700 --> 01:32:44.380
[Guest 2]: countries, Amit, where they have taught very well about what their welfare state's architecture

01:32:44.380 --> 01:32:49.420
[Guest 2]: ought to be like. China is one of them. Brazil is one of them. We can learn a lot from these

01:32:49.420 --> 01:32:54.940
[Guest 2]: countries. They have very different instruments, they use co-financed models of welfare. So there's

01:32:54.940 --> 01:33:00.380
[Guest 2]: social insurance as one example, in combination with certain things, which are universal transfers.

01:33:00.380 --> 01:33:03.820
[Guest 2]: We just, and I think this goes back to that point that I had made, I mean, if there's one sort of

01:33:03.820 --> 01:33:10.700
[Guest 2]: dream reform in my mind, it is a very clear articulation fiscally, as well as between

01:33:10.700 --> 01:33:15.420
[Guest 2]: center state relations on what is the welfare architecture of India. Are you going to continue

01:33:15.420 --> 01:33:20.940
[Guest 2]: to have 464 schemes? Or do you want to learn from an Indonesia and maybe say, well, we'll have 10

01:33:20.940 --> 01:33:26.620
[Guest 2]: big national schemes, NREGA and PDS, one of them. PMJ is one of them, PM Kisan is one, I'm just

01:33:26.620 --> 01:33:31.500
[Guest 2]: throwing that out. And maybe the rest we do as untied grants to states and let states then decide.

01:33:31.500 --> 01:33:35.020
[Guest 2]: And then that sort of harmoniously manages some of the center state politics as well.

01:33:35.020 --> 01:33:40.620
[Guest 2]: There are ways to do this. Again, one looks at the energy and enthusiasm. So to me, Amit, I think

01:33:40.620 --> 01:33:48.620
[Guest 2]: what I think we should retire is this idea that there is this conflict between welfare redistribution

01:33:49.260 --> 01:33:54.460
[Guest 2]: and certain growth dividends when it comes to more productive assets and public goods provision.

01:33:54.460 --> 01:33:58.620
[Guest 2]: Actually, there are studies coming out of, be it sub-Saharan Africa, be it Latin America,

01:33:58.620 --> 01:34:03.580
[Guest 2]: which show that if you do both carefully and together, they work very well. They're mutually

01:34:03.580 --> 01:34:09.260
[Guest 2]: reinforcing because if you give people a basic level of cash, for example, there is psychological

01:34:09.260 --> 01:34:14.060
[Guest 2]: assurance that you can take on risks in your businesses. You can take on risks in the jobs

01:34:14.060 --> 01:34:21.100
[Guest 2]: that you'll do. You can invest in education. They're both mutually reinforcing paradigms.

01:34:21.100 --> 01:34:25.660
[Guest 2]: But the question is, you need a policy articulation on what the balance between the two is.

01:34:25.660 --> 01:34:29.260
[Guest 2]: I think it's the Finance Commission, actually, where this needs to be articulated.

01:34:29.260 --> 01:34:32.860
[Guest 2]: They've done it quite well when it comes to disaster response funds. There's a very clear

01:34:32.860 --> 01:34:37.100
[Guest 2]: articulation of how that will be done. It worked quite well during the pandemic because state

01:34:37.100 --> 01:34:42.300
[Guest 2]: disaster response funds were being used to actually respond to local crises, because local

01:34:42.300 --> 01:34:46.700
[Guest 2]: crises are going to be very different. The national government can't manage it. We need to think very

01:34:46.700 --> 01:34:51.020
[Guest 2]: carefully similarly around the welfare question. So I don't disagree with, I think, in fact, what

01:34:51.020 --> 01:34:56.620
[Guest 2]: your concern is. I share that concern. But to me, I think what I think we should not think of is that

01:34:56.620 --> 01:35:02.780
[Guest 2]: the two are in conflict. I think there has to be a very clear policy path, much like in other

01:35:02.780 --> 01:35:08.140
[Guest 2]: countries where they are not in conflict and they're cyclical. Because what is NREGA? NREGA

01:35:08.140 --> 01:35:11.900
[Guest 2]: is not an anti-poverty program. I mean, people think it's that. It's actually a shock responsive

01:35:11.900 --> 01:35:15.580
[Guest 2]: safety net. So if you're in the middle of a shock, if you're dealing with something, you respond.

01:35:15.580 --> 01:35:19.900
[Guest 2]: We can argue whether it actually responds in some places and it doesn't in others based on

01:35:19.900 --> 01:35:24.540
[Guest 2]: local capacity. But I think you need to think very carefully about what are the different

01:35:24.540 --> 01:35:28.780
[Guest 2]: instruments of welfare you're putting in. It has to be a balance. You know, often, and now I realize

01:35:28.780 --> 01:35:32.460
[Guest 2]: I'm going into a rant on welfare policy and I will try and be brief, but there are three

01:35:32.460 --> 01:35:37.900
[Guest 2]: instruments of welfare. One is what we call protective measures, which is after you have

01:35:37.900 --> 01:35:44.220
[Guest 2]: fallen into poverty, it protects the poor, right, that you won't fall further below in your income.

01:35:44.220 --> 01:35:50.460
[Guest 2]: So it's almost exposed. There are preventive measures, which tend to be much more co-financed

01:35:50.460 --> 01:35:55.500
[Guest 2]: because essentially you use your money now to save for a crisis in the future, so social insurance.

01:35:55.500 --> 01:35:59.740
[Guest 2]: And there are promotional measures, so that's skill training, livelihoods programs, all these kinds of

01:35:59.740 --> 01:36:06.060
[Guest 2]: things. If you look at countries that have a healthy fiscal balance, right, of welfare, they use the

01:36:06.060 --> 01:36:12.060
[Guest 2]: three based on what the local economy looks like. So, you know, context where they are relying much

01:36:12.060 --> 01:36:17.740
[Guest 2]: more on agriculture, very susceptible to drought. You'll see, you know, crop insurance mixed with

01:36:17.740 --> 01:36:23.660
[Guest 2]: food rations within NREGA, right, like some example like that. India actually has, you know, the great

01:36:23.660 --> 01:36:28.140
[Guest 2]: privilege of having all these different contexts because right now we have a welfare context where

01:36:28.140 --> 01:36:34.300
[Guest 2]: you have the same welfare programs running in urban, well, Maharashtra as well as Delhi.

01:36:35.180 --> 01:36:39.740
[Guest 2]: That makes no sense because actually even the amount of transfers that you need to give people

01:36:39.740 --> 01:36:45.340
[Guest 2]: are very different based on local consumption baskets, local minimum wage. We have no policy

01:36:45.340 --> 01:36:51.340
[Guest 2]: articulation right now on how to tackle this balance. And I think to me it's going to be one

01:36:51.340 --> 01:36:56.220
[Guest 2]: of the most important questions as economists, politicians, anyone in the sort of technocratic

01:36:56.220 --> 01:37:01.260
[Guest 2]: welfare domain space. Right now I know we're in this political moment where everybody wants deeper

01:37:01.260 --> 01:37:05.020
[Guest 2]: transfers and support because there are some communities that are hurting. But I actually

01:37:05.020 --> 01:37:09.420
[Guest 2]: think the really important question is to think about how do we move from just thinking of it as

01:37:09.420 --> 01:37:14.620
[Guest 2]: just transfers to thinking of it as a policy path which is fiscally sustainable so that those

01:37:14.620 --> 01:37:19.500
[Guest 2]: conflicts can be ironed out a bit. Or you have platforms just like GST, you have platforms which

01:37:19.500 --> 01:37:24.380
[Guest 2]: are center state which can organize then if there are conflicts which might happen. I think that's

01:37:24.380 --> 01:37:30.140
[Guest 1]: really the need of the hour. I think one thing that I completely agree with, Amit, is that I

01:37:30.140 --> 01:37:36.860
[Guest 1]: think poverty is a bigger problem than inequality. And I think when we focus too much on inequality

01:37:36.860 --> 01:37:43.180
[Guest 1]: then we are trying to solve a problem using policy actions and measures which may not necessarily

01:37:43.180 --> 01:37:49.100
[Guest 1]: address inequality and it creates a lot of other distortions in the process. And I think there's

01:37:49.100 --> 01:37:55.820
[Guest 1]: unambiguous evidence from the history of economic growth so to speak that the one thing that really

01:37:55.820 --> 01:38:01.100
[Guest 1]: works in terms of uplifting people from poverty and improving their living standards is growth.

01:38:01.100 --> 01:38:05.420
[Guest 1]: And there are, for example, my favorite examples of four countries which have made the transition

01:38:05.420 --> 01:38:10.300
[Guest 1]: from a developing country status to an OECD developed country status which is Israel,

01:38:10.300 --> 01:38:16.540
[Guest 1]: Chile, South Korea, and Taiwan. And none of them did this using purely a redistributive model of

01:38:16.540 --> 01:38:22.220
[Guest 1]: development so to speak. I mean they exclusively focused on growth promoting measures which was

01:38:22.220 --> 01:38:26.380
[Guest 1]: supported by the governments and that is what helped them to make the transitions. I think

01:38:26.380 --> 01:38:31.340
[Guest 1]: there is no running away from the fact that the most important thing we need to be focusing on

01:38:31.340 --> 01:38:36.140
[Guest 1]: is growth and that is what's going to help over a period of time to alleviate poverty which is

01:38:36.140 --> 01:38:40.140
[Guest 1]: what has happened over the last several decades barring the last few years when even growth itself

01:38:40.140 --> 01:38:45.100
[Guest 1]: has stalled in India. And I think by focusing too much on inequality and there is a trade-off.

01:38:45.100 --> 01:38:50.380
[Guest 1]: The trade-off is because the fiscal resources of the government are finite and the reason they are

01:38:50.380 --> 01:38:56.860
[Guest 1]: also finite is because once you are struggling on growth you're automatically your tax to GDP

01:38:56.860 --> 01:39:02.060
[Guest 1]: ratio which is what the measure of fiscal prowess of the government is that gets compromised right.

01:39:02.060 --> 01:39:07.180
[Guest 1]: If you're not able to sort of increase the tax base then you are limited to a certain finite

01:39:07.180 --> 01:39:11.820
[Guest 1]: amount of tax to GDP and if you're not able to enlarge it then you're sort of trying to choose

01:39:11.820 --> 01:39:16.460
[Guest 1]: between I have 100 rupees what do I allocate this 100 rupees to. I have to do this 460 for

01:39:16.460 --> 01:39:20.460
[Guest 1]: welfare schemes. I have to do public good provision. I also have to do other things

01:39:20.460 --> 01:39:26.060
[Guest 1]: and I think the Indian state is really very badly stretched out in thousands of directions right. I

01:39:26.060 --> 01:39:30.060
[Guest 1]: mean they are trying to do some rudimentary provision of public good and struggling at that.

01:39:30.060 --> 01:39:33.740
[Guest 1]: They're trying to do welfare schemes they're struggling at that and they are doing many

01:39:33.740 --> 01:39:37.180
[Guest 1]: other things that they should not be doing and of course struggling at that right. So you have

01:39:37.180 --> 01:39:42.940
[Guest 1]: this really finite limited fiscal resources which are being pulled at from multiple angles and then

01:39:42.940 --> 01:39:47.180
[Guest 1]: you're choosing that what fire am I going to put out and what battle am I going to fight and what's

01:39:47.180 --> 01:39:51.340
[Guest 1]: going to give me the highest returns in terms of let's say winning elections and staying in power.

01:39:51.340 --> 01:39:56.060
[Guest 1]: And in the process what definitely gets compromised is growth because the state is doing

01:39:56.620 --> 01:40:01.100
[Guest 1]: a thousand things which are inimical to growth in the country and they need to figure out that okay

01:40:01.100 --> 01:40:06.940
[Guest 1]: let's take a step back from all of these things and let growth take its course and yes when there

01:40:06.940 --> 01:40:11.500
[Guest 1]: are rare events when there are catastrophic events we need to have the budget to spend at that point

01:40:11.500 --> 01:40:15.740
[Guest 1]: of time which is what the government was not able to do this time because for years you've just been

01:40:15.740 --> 01:40:20.300
[Guest 1]: on a spending spree and when the time comes for you to actually provide the stimulus and the

01:40:20.300 --> 01:40:25.180
[Guest 1]: support needed you're suddenly worried about fiscal deficit and debt. So the entire thinking

01:40:25.180 --> 01:40:30.540
[Guest 1]: about how do you support the economy in bad times how do you sort of step back and build a surplus

01:40:30.540 --> 01:40:35.500
[Guest 1]: during good times and how do you step away from this interfering into the growth which should be

01:40:35.500 --> 01:40:40.540
[Guest 1]: the job of the private sector that entire thinking has gone haywire and I think to a large extent

01:40:41.100 --> 01:40:46.300
[Guest 1]: we tend to obsess about inequality right and what inequality does I think it normalizes envy

01:40:46.300 --> 01:40:50.060
[Guest 1]: right I mean there is this thing that okay if the rich are getting richer we should be envious

01:40:50.060 --> 01:40:57.180
[Guest 1]: of that and that's just a very suboptimal outcome so to speak so for example when I teach my child

01:40:57.180 --> 01:41:01.500
[Guest 1]: or the values that I want to inculcate I don't want to tell her that be envious of the other

01:41:01.500 --> 01:41:06.220
[Guest 1]: kids in the building or the school I want to tell her that look at your own life in absolute terms

01:41:06.220 --> 01:41:10.700
[Guest 1]: build your own character and do the things that's going to make you happy irrespective of whether

01:41:10.700 --> 01:41:15.340
[Guest 1]: what the other person next to you is doing but therefore I think inequality it's the state of

01:41:15.340 --> 01:41:19.740
[Guest 1]: the nature there's inequality everywhere and I think at some point we just have to stop obsessing

01:41:19.740 --> 01:41:25.020
[Guest 1]: about the fact that economic policy actions should be catered towards addressing inequality we should

01:41:25.020 --> 01:41:32.140
[Guest 1]: focus on growth and and that is going to lead to the alleviation of poverty one thing that I do

01:41:32.140 --> 01:41:38.860
[Guest 1]: want to focus on here is I think there should be qualitative opportunities so more than income

01:41:38.860 --> 01:41:43.900
[Guest 1]: inequality or wealth inequality etc it's the qualitative opportunities that probably should

01:41:43.900 --> 01:41:48.700
[Guest 1]: receive a lot more focus on discussion and that is where again we fail because the state is being

01:41:48.700 --> 01:41:55.180
[Guest 2]: squeezed into multiple directions yeah I just want to say a couple of things one I want to just

01:41:55.180 --> 01:42:02.780
[Guest 2]: push on this idea I don't think there is a growth versus distribution a redistribution trade-off I

01:42:02.780 --> 01:42:07.820
[Guest 2]: know this is something in a very traditional sense in economics I think we're taught this

01:42:07.820 --> 01:42:14.620
[Guest 2]: taught this but actually there's a lot of work that's coming out of and I'm particularly thinking

01:42:14.620 --> 01:42:19.740
[Guest 2]: of poor economics is about this right I mean there's an entire section of thinking about

01:42:19.740 --> 01:42:27.660
[Guest 2]: very careful rigorous experiments which show assets plus counseling short-term transfers

01:42:27.660 --> 01:42:33.500
[Guest 2]: lead to businesses that grow which then there are long-run spillover effects on the local economy

01:42:33.500 --> 01:42:39.180
[Guest 2]: right so I do want to sort of push this idea that you know one of the big reasons why there's this

01:42:39.180 --> 01:42:44.860
[Guest 2]: whole conversation on the basic income for example is this idea that in a precarious labor market you

01:42:44.860 --> 01:42:50.860
[Guest 2]: want some minimum assurance for everyone so that everyone has the access to one fairly large part

01:42:50.860 --> 01:42:56.700
[Guest 2]: of a significant transfer in India it may not need to go to everybody you could say it goes to say

01:42:56.700 --> 01:43:02.140
[Guest 2]: 80 percent of the informal economy for example and then at least with that assurance you're able to

01:43:02.140 --> 01:43:06.060
[Guest 2]: as we say partake in risk-taking behavior all kinds of you know economic goods which are good

01:43:06.060 --> 01:43:13.900
[Guest 2]: for growth I don't necessarily see them in conflict if there is a very clear coherent policy in place

01:43:14.460 --> 01:43:19.580
[Guest 2]: around social protection which I would agree right now doesn't exist in India I think the two can be

01:43:19.580 --> 01:43:25.260
[Amit Varma]: consonant and they can be enforcing I think if I can sort of push back on the pushback I would

01:43:25.260 --> 01:43:33.980
[Amit Varma]: sort of say that one I agree that in theory they may not be as much of a dichotomy as it may seem

01:43:33.980 --> 01:43:39.660
[Amit Varma]: that you can have what you as you described it a policy path where you can have a some welfare

01:43:39.660 --> 01:43:44.540
[Amit Varma]: policies happening and also growth happening however what happens in practice and what

01:43:44.540 --> 01:43:49.020
[Amit Varma]: happens in the political mindset and what happened you know what happens when it comes to scarce

01:43:49.020 --> 01:43:56.700
[Amit Varma]: resources as Rajeshwari said is that there inevitably is a dichotomy in the sense that

01:43:56.700 --> 01:44:02.460
[Amit Varma]: you will always privilege welfare policies more number one because they're much easier to sell

01:44:02.460 --> 01:44:09.020
[Amit Varma]: it's much easier to tell a voter that I'm giving you something as opposed to telling him that I'm

01:44:09.020 --> 01:44:13.900
[Amit Varma]: going to do a structural reform which will pay off in 10 years and blah blah blah so in political

01:44:13.900 --> 01:44:18.380
[Amit Varma]: sense all your incentives are towards just going for the welfare schemes whether you call them

01:44:18.380 --> 01:44:24.780
[Amit Varma]: handouts or freebies or whatever you're giving something directly and also that then becomes a

01:44:24.780 --> 01:44:29.580
[Amit Varma]: cop-out that then becomes a way for you to say that I have done everything I could and it becomes

01:44:29.580 --> 01:44:34.700
[Amit Varma]: a race to the bottom as it has with farm loan waivers and you use it to not address any of the

01:44:34.700 --> 01:44:39.500
[Amit Varma]: core problems the way I look at it as this is that let's say I have a terrible backache at my lower

01:44:39.500 --> 01:44:44.860
[Amit Varma]: back right the immediate thing is to give me an anesthetic to give me a crocene or if it's more

01:44:44.860 --> 01:44:51.820
[Amit Varma]: severe to give me a good painkiller and that then you know relieves me of that pain but the point is

01:44:51.820 --> 01:44:55.980
[Amit Varma]: you're not actually treating the disease what if I have pancreatic cancer which you know a lower

01:44:55.980 --> 01:44:59.980
[Amit Varma]: back pain is one of the signs of you know you're not creating or treating the disease and you're

01:44:59.980 --> 01:45:04.780
[Amit Varma]: also saying that oh I gave you something you know your pain is better I'm doing my job so that's

01:45:04.780 --> 01:45:11.900
[Amit Varma]: really my worry there which is not to argue for one or the other what I would say is that I'm

01:45:11.900 --> 01:45:17.660
[Amit Varma]: completely okay my worry is that we just think of welfarism all the time even this current

01:45:17.660 --> 01:45:24.620
[Amit Varma]: dispensation has realized that they can rely on well-delivered welfarism to take their eyes off

01:45:24.620 --> 01:45:30.060
[Amit Varma]: the broader ball where they can do nonsense like demonetization and the botched up GST and so on

01:45:30.060 --> 01:45:35.020
[Guest 1]: and no one holds them accountable as Rajeshwari pointed out. So two points I'll make and over to

01:45:35.020 --> 01:45:40.620
[Guest 1]: you then Shaina so one is that I think you know theoretically it makes sense to say that we'll do

01:45:40.620 --> 01:45:45.420
[Guest 1]: a basic income scheme where we only target the most deserving and the needy people or let's say

01:45:45.420 --> 01:45:50.540
[Guest 1]: x percentage of the population but I think to execute something like that requires an enormous

01:45:50.540 --> 01:45:56.380
[Guest 1]: level of sophisticated state capacity where you identify who the exact recipients who are deserving

01:45:56.380 --> 01:46:01.340
[Guest 1]: are going to receive it then ensure that there's not going to be any leakage so I think that I

01:46:01.340 --> 01:46:05.900
[Guest 1]: don't think we even have anywhere remotely that kind of state capacity and I think what happens

01:46:05.900 --> 01:46:11.020
[Guest 1]: is once you have 460 for welfare schemes it's very difficult to withdraw any scheme because

01:46:11.020 --> 01:46:15.660
[Guest 1]: all the incentive is then to is to pile on more and more schemes rather than withdraw anything

01:46:15.660 --> 01:46:19.740
[Guest 1]: clean up the system and just say that we are only going to stick to one scheme because fiscally we

01:46:19.740 --> 01:46:24.700
[Guest 1]: are constrained I don't think that ever happens in reality and lastly I think what this government

01:46:24.700 --> 01:46:29.100
[Guest 1]: has done is that I think they've cleaned up the last mile delivery much better than the previous

01:46:29.100 --> 01:46:33.260
[Guest 1]: government so I think while there are still leakages but the last mile delivery has significantly

01:46:33.260 --> 01:46:38.380
[Guest 1]: become better and that again goes going back to my original point that is where the accountability

01:46:38.380 --> 01:46:42.140
[Guest 1]: system becomes even more problematic because if I'm actually getting the delivery of the welfare

01:46:42.140 --> 01:46:46.540
[Guest 1]: schemes better than what I used to before in my mind this government is doing better than

01:46:46.540 --> 01:46:50.300
[Guest 1]: the previous government right and therefore what am I going to really hold this government

01:46:50.300 --> 01:46:56.060
[Guest 1]: accountable for so and and lastly I think the countries which have which have a welfarist

01:46:56.060 --> 01:47:01.420
[Guest 1]: social state with the successful redistributive policy are also the ones which have very high

01:47:01.420 --> 01:47:07.260
[Guest 1]: levels of GDP and per capita income because that generates the fiscal resources that you would need

01:47:07.260 --> 01:47:12.460
[Guest 1]: in order to continue and sustain an efficient redistribution program and also you have social

01:47:12.460 --> 01:47:16.620
[Guest 1]: spending on health care and education I mean look at Indian government the pandemic exposed it

01:47:16.620 --> 01:47:20.620
[Guest 1]: less than two percent of the GDP is being spent on the health care but you have a whole lot of

01:47:20.620 --> 01:47:25.180
[Guest 1]: welfare schemes but that's the palliative that Amit was mentioning about okay a couple of things

01:47:25.180 --> 01:47:30.140
[Guest 2]: one India spends about two percent of GDP on all of its welfare schemes so again this goes back to

01:47:30.140 --> 01:47:34.780
[Guest 2]: fact I think we keep thinking that in fact in our mind I think we think the Indian government spends

01:47:34.780 --> 01:47:38.540
[Guest 2]: much more on welfare than it actually does so that's the first thing and I think for those

01:47:38.540 --> 01:47:42.620
[Guest 2]: who are interested in the breakdown on this we have the World Bank and the IMF have a series

01:47:42.620 --> 01:47:47.500
[Guest 2]: of reports I've authored some of them looking at budgets so I think it's not the case in fact

01:47:47.500 --> 01:47:52.300
[Guest 2]: we're spending health and education certainly you could spend more but it's not that there's a

01:47:52.300 --> 01:47:56.380
[Guest 2]: trade-off between spending more on education spending on welfare because that's not happening

01:47:56.380 --> 01:48:00.700
[Guest 2]: never has happened in our politics number one number two I think on the question of targeting

01:48:00.700 --> 01:48:06.780
[Guest 2]: actually I mean I work on targeting in fact the public distribution system and when the pandemic

01:48:06.780 --> 01:48:13.260
[Guest 2]: hit PMGKY showed you have the Jan Dhan Yojana you have the public distribution system they are near

01:48:13.260 --> 01:48:18.220
[Guest 2]: universal we have a paper for those who are interested it's called from intent to implementation

01:48:18.220 --> 01:48:25.500
[Guest 2]: it uses CMI data to track what happened with PMGKY transfers and what we essentially find is not just

01:48:25.500 --> 01:48:30.300
[Guest 2]: us there are others who've done surveys and what we find is the PDS distribution system actually in

01:48:30.300 --> 01:48:34.460
[Guest 2]: terms of identifying targeting is extremely effective because it's universal and it's

01:48:34.460 --> 01:48:39.020
[Guest 2]: constantly being used and one of the things that people like Rajesh Bansal who used to be in fact

01:48:39.020 --> 01:48:44.140
[Guest 2]: briefly at the RBI was with the DBT mission essentially wrote a paper saying why don't we

01:48:44.140 --> 01:48:49.740
[Guest 2]: create a who to pay database using the PDS so actually to your point about targeting and basic

01:48:49.740 --> 01:48:56.380
[Guest 2]: income in fact now in policy conversations that I am part of one constantly hears the lament that

01:48:56.380 --> 01:49:03.420
[Guest 2]: this is so easy to do and it would also then put a squeeze on the remaining 464 why don't we start

01:49:03.420 --> 01:49:08.620
[Guest 2]: to move in that direction and some states have so Tamil Nadu for instance is using the PDS to

01:49:08.620 --> 01:49:12.460
[Guest 2]: essentially do an income transfer there are other states that are going to start to move in that

01:49:12.460 --> 01:49:18.060
[Guest 2]: direction so actually I think that the execution of at least some of the basic income stuff is

01:49:18.060 --> 01:49:24.220
[Amit Varma]: much more doable so I'm really glad we are all agreed on one thing one what a relief it is that

01:49:24.220 --> 01:49:29.100
[Amit Varma]: that damn drilling noise has stopped I'm sorry dear listeners what happened was that suddenly

01:49:29.100 --> 01:49:33.900
[Amit Varma]: unexpectedly and this never happens there was some drilling at an apartment upstairs or downstairs

01:49:33.900 --> 01:49:37.900
[Amit Varma]: which you heard so I went to the two flats upstairs the two flats above that then the two

01:49:37.900 --> 01:49:42.620
[Amit Varma]: flats below me and finally two floors below me there were people who were drilling and they

01:49:42.620 --> 01:49:47.900
[Amit Varma]: kindly offered to stop drilling they did not understand recording so I had to tell them I'm

01:49:47.900 --> 01:49:54.780
[Amit Varma]: live with BBC to London and I'm going to lose a lot of money please I really did say that and

01:49:54.780 --> 01:49:59.500
[Amit Varma]: then we kind of managed to sort of make them stop the drilling so I hope this episode is worth it

01:49:59.500 --> 01:50:06.460
[Amit Varma]: now yeah so I mean the lot of thought-provoking stuff on welfare and growth to think about and

01:50:06.460 --> 01:50:11.740
[Amit Varma]: what I'm glad about is at the fundamental level we are on the same page growth is important there's

01:50:11.740 --> 01:50:17.100
[Amit Varma]: no getting away from it and in the short term you know if you can alleviate the pain of people

01:50:17.100 --> 01:50:21.180
[Amit Varma]: that's a good thing and it must be done unfortunately this is often seen in dichotomous

01:50:21.180 --> 01:50:25.580
[Amit Varma]: terms and my worry is that it ends up being a dichotomy in the political level but leave that

01:50:25.580 --> 01:50:31.660
[Amit Varma]: aside I want to actually now you know before we go to the break and we begin with and after that

01:50:31.660 --> 01:50:36.300
[Amit Varma]: we'll talk about your life Rajeshwari you are not getting away from that but before that I want to

01:50:36.300 --> 01:50:41.020
[Amit Varma]: bring up one of the twitter questions because I think it leads us to an interesting area that

01:50:41.020 --> 01:50:47.740
[Amit Varma]: both of you alluded to and a couple of questions Raghuram Janak asks where did we in brackets India

01:50:47.740 --> 01:50:52.940
[Amit Varma]: go wrong economically in the last eight years and what should be the key area of focus going forward

01:50:52.940 --> 01:50:57.820
[Amit Varma]: that's Raghuram Janak and Jordan Khosrow which is a delightful name by the way though on twitter

01:50:57.820 --> 01:51:03.020
[Amit Varma]: you never know if it's the real name it you know no one on the internet knows I'm a dog you've

01:51:03.020 --> 01:51:08.620
[Amit Varma]: seen that old cartoon I think it's a new yorker cartoon yeah no but we're not calling Jordan a

01:51:08.620 --> 01:51:13.980
[Amit Varma]: dog I'm just saying it's a nice name and he asked when did India's economic decline start was it

01:51:13.980 --> 01:51:19.660
[Amit Varma]: during Mughals or during British Raj or earlier than that stop quote and I'll attempt a brief

01:51:19.660 --> 01:51:25.020
[Amit Varma]: answer to that and saying that no you don't need to go so far back the truth is that our economic

01:51:25.020 --> 01:51:30.460
[Amit Varma]: governance has been miserable for most of our history there was a golden 20-year period from

01:51:30.460 --> 01:51:37.180
[Amit Varma]: 1991 to 2011 when things were looking up and were moving in the right direction and for the last

01:51:37.180 --> 01:51:42.380
[Amit Varma]: 10 11 years or so it's been a disaster I've got an episode with Pooja Mehra called the lost decade

01:51:42.380 --> 01:51:47.820
[Amit Varma]: um on her book about you know how all of this happened she takes you into the weeds and you

01:51:47.820 --> 01:51:52.700
[Amit Varma]: get to learn exactly in terms of policy what went wrong and it started going wrong before this

01:51:52.700 --> 01:51:56.540
[Amit Varma]: particular dispension and this particular dispension of course made it much worse for

01:51:56.540 --> 01:52:01.900
[Amit Varma]: reasons Rajeshwari mentioned like demonetization the boss GST and so on and I've also done an

01:52:01.900 --> 01:52:08.700
[Amit Varma]: episode on the 1991 reforms about why we did have that 20 year old golden period and you know in

01:52:08.700 --> 01:52:13.420
[Amit Varma]: in terms of specific policies and how our way of thinking changed you know and and the point that

01:52:13.420 --> 01:52:19.260
[Amit Varma]: I want to underscore here is that a number of the questions are also talking about how right-wing

01:52:19.260 --> 01:52:25.740
[Amit Varma]: economists have gone wrong and I feel that this is people conflate Modi's economic policies with

01:52:25.740 --> 01:52:29.100
[Amit Varma]: right-wing just because socially it's called right-wing I think the spectrum of left and

01:52:29.100 --> 01:52:34.540
[Amit Varma]: right in India doesn't really work but if you really look at it all of India's economics except

01:52:34.540 --> 01:52:40.300
[Amit Varma]: for parts of the 20-year period have been statist and therefore left-wing in a sense markets haven't

01:52:40.300 --> 01:52:45.580
[Amit Varma]: been allowed to play I had the congress politician Salman soz on the show and Salman said that in

01:52:45.580 --> 01:52:53.020
[Amit Varma]: 2014 when Modi won he was actually optimistic because of the noises Modi had made about freeing

01:52:53.020 --> 01:52:57.580
[Amit Varma]: up markets and getting away from statism Modi did nothing of that he doubled down on policies of

01:52:57.580 --> 01:53:02.620
[Amit Varma]: the past he showed the top-down central planning of Nehru he showed the authoritarian streak of

01:53:03.660 --> 01:53:09.180
[Amit Varma]: Indira if anything the ruthlessness of Sanjay Gandhi even and so on and so forth which is why

01:53:09.180 --> 01:53:15.660
[Amit Varma]: we are in this mess so this perception that some people have that oh you know left-wing versus

01:53:15.660 --> 01:53:21.740
[Amit Varma]: right-wing in economics it's all fundamentally statist and there is no freedom at all in fact

01:53:21.740 --> 01:53:27.740
[Amit Varma]: all our parties are left on economics and right on social issues as Arun Shourie famously said

01:53:27.740 --> 01:53:33.980
[Amit Varma]: you know a UPA is equal to NDA plus cow and of course these days I think what we sort of

01:53:33.980 --> 01:53:40.140
[Amit Varma]: need to worry about is a cow aspect of it of how our society is torn apart and there was

01:53:40.140 --> 01:53:45.420
[Amit Varma]: another question from twitter from a gentleman named Rohit Ripati saying how long can economists

01:53:45.420 --> 01:53:50.700
[Amit Varma]: ignore the coming apart of the social fabric it's a serious question and to this I just want to say

01:53:50.700 --> 01:53:56.780
[Amit Varma]: that hey economists are not ignoring any coming apart of the social fabric economists are people

01:53:56.780 --> 01:54:03.020
[Amit Varma]: just like people are and every economist I know is you know aghast at it and there's another

01:54:03.020 --> 01:54:07.180
[Amit Varma]: question which this is a good time to address where someone I won't name because I'm going to

01:54:07.180 --> 01:54:11.420
[Amit Varma]: diss the question I asked about you know what question should I ask you guys and this person

01:54:11.420 --> 01:54:15.420
[Amit Varma]: said quote ask them what they were doing in the Neeti Aayog when this government ran down the

01:54:15.420 --> 01:54:21.660
[Amit Varma]: economy into pieces ask why did they whitewash Modi stop good why did you guys whitewash Modi

01:54:21.660 --> 01:54:26.140
[Amit Varma]: I have absolutely no idea what you're talking about at this point of time I think this

01:54:26.140 --> 01:54:32.220
[Amit Varma]: particular gentleman just saw the word economist and got enraged and triggered by that and went

01:54:32.220 --> 01:54:37.820
[Amit Varma]: off into this rant and the truth is that I actually have a filter for who I allow on the

01:54:37.820 --> 01:54:42.620
[Amit Varma]: show and one of my litmus tests is that if you supported demonetization you are never coming

01:54:42.620 --> 01:54:48.620
[Amit Varma]: on the show right I made one quasi exception for Arvind Subramaniam and I asked him all the tough

01:54:48.620 --> 01:54:53.900
[Amit Varma]: questions so if anyone feels that I don't ask stuff don't get those people on and and we had

01:54:53.900 --> 01:54:58.620
[Amit Varma]: a very civil conversation but I asked all the tough questions including about demon I think

01:54:58.620 --> 01:55:03.580
[Guest 1]: there is a huge amount of simplification that's happening here right I mean the word economist

01:55:03.580 --> 01:55:09.340
[Guest 1]: is getting conflated with there's just this one kind of an entity who works for the government

01:55:09.340 --> 01:55:14.140
[Guest 1]: in a government thing that supports all the policies that's coming out of the PMO or the

01:55:14.140 --> 01:55:19.020
[Guest 1]: MOF and not protesting all the bad things that's happening there's some kind of a non-existent

01:55:19.020 --> 01:55:23.420
[Amit Varma]: entity that's in the minds of people no I remember at the time of demon I wrote this

01:55:23.420 --> 01:55:28.460
[Amit Varma]: strong editorial about useful idiots Lenin's phrase not literally calling people's idiots

01:55:28.460 --> 01:55:33.260
[Amit Varma]: where I said any economist who support demonetization is either a bad economist or a

01:55:33.260 --> 01:55:38.140
[Amit Varma]: bad human being and I kind of stand by that and every economist I would lean more towards the

01:55:38.140 --> 01:55:43.260
[Amit Varma]: latter more towards yeah me too exactly exactly I completely agree because all the examples who

01:55:43.260 --> 01:55:48.300
[Guest 1]: come to my mind are bad human beings to begin with demonetization was an event that almost split the

01:55:48.300 --> 01:55:51.740
[Guest 1]: world into there are two kinds of people right I mean those who support those who don't absolutely

01:55:51.740 --> 01:55:55.980
[Guest 1]: it became crystal clear and since then it has just been a slippery slope no and also I think

01:55:55.980 --> 01:56:00.060
[Amit Varma]: you know what I mean I don't know if one should be held culpable for it but there's also a failure

01:56:00.060 --> 01:56:04.620
[Amit Varma]: on the part of economists like most the majority of economists basically almost all economists

01:56:04.620 --> 01:56:10.300
[Amit Varma]: opposed it because it is batshit crazy as my friend southern and who misses yes it's batshit

01:56:10.300 --> 01:56:16.300
[Amit Varma]: yes right and yet there is a public perception that oh the economist supported Modiji all of

01:56:16.300 --> 01:56:21.980
[Guest 2]: which are completely untrue yeah and you know but I'll tell you something and I wrote a piece

01:56:21.980 --> 01:56:29.020
[Guest 2]: in fact at the end of last year about this so I go to a lot of Delhi parties right and this I

01:56:29.020 --> 01:56:33.500
[Guest 2]: think goes back to this gentleman who was so enraged with the use of the phrase economist

01:56:33.500 --> 01:56:38.780
[Guest 2]: I go to a lot of Delhi parties and this was a new year's thing and I'd been and I was generally

01:56:38.780 --> 01:56:42.780
[Guest 2]: talking to someone and because as we know I'm a nerd I have really nothing else to talk to people

01:56:42.780 --> 01:56:48.780
[Guest 2]: about other than the economy and numbers right I have really nothing else and so I was talking to

01:56:48.780 --> 01:56:53.660
[Guest 2]: some gentlemen in their 50s who for some reason all of them have a crush on Milind Soman I want

01:56:53.660 --> 01:56:59.500
[Guest 2]: everyone to know this gentleman in his 50s Amit Rajeshwari let me tell you in north India now

01:56:59.500 --> 01:57:04.940
[Guest 2]: amongst the elite gents this is something I believe men in their 50s they all want to be

01:57:04.940 --> 01:57:11.020
[Guest 2]: as fit as Milind Soman is now that he is in his 50s and I think they also aspire to like all his

01:57:11.020 --> 01:57:15.980
[Guest 2]: triathlete abilities and all of that it's a good thing to aspire to I suppose I suppose even I

01:57:15.980 --> 01:57:22.540
[Guest 2]: would like to look like Milind Soman I know it's kind of not possible okay I mean I have other

01:57:22.540 --> 01:57:27.660
[Guest 2]: thoughts which I will keep to myself for the time being but the point being I remember I started

01:57:27.660 --> 01:57:33.660
[Guest 2]: someone asked me what I did and I mentioned that I am an economist at the world bank immediately

01:57:33.660 --> 01:57:41.900
[Guest 2]: there was this sniggering cynicism and they said oh but you're and they said this in Hindi in almost

01:57:41.900 --> 01:57:47.740
[Guest 2]: half the Punjabi they said but you're an economist what will you know about the economy and that is

01:57:47.740 --> 01:57:54.220
[Guest 2]: I think the current rep of the community and I completely agree with Rajeshwari I think it is a

01:57:54.220 --> 01:57:59.820
[Guest 2]: it's a strange kind of morphing of who you think an economist is but the other thing that makes it

01:57:59.820 --> 01:58:06.940
[Guest 2]: really complicated is that these were gentlemen who are all running businesses and they felt and

01:58:06.940 --> 01:58:11.820
[Guest 2]: this I think goes back to also the point that Amit was making about how much we make economics

01:58:11.820 --> 01:58:18.140
[Guest 2]: accessible in the way people think about the world all these guys seem to believe that they had the

01:58:18.140 --> 01:58:23.500
[Guest 2]: pulse on the real economy because they hired people they were fighting with their workers

01:58:23.500 --> 01:58:29.260
[Guest 2]: they were producing things and they said we know and what do you know and I think there is this

01:58:29.260 --> 01:58:34.460
[Guest 2]: competition now we do live in this post-truth world there are competitions about who gets to

01:58:34.460 --> 01:58:40.380
[Guest 2]: assert what fact and how facts are constructed and I think honestly when I was sitting there

01:58:40.380 --> 01:58:45.260
[Guest 2]: I mean at this particular social gathering I realized it's very difficult because what I can

01:58:45.260 --> 01:58:51.420
[Guest 2]: now share with them they will just dismiss as technicalese you know this is just don't bore

01:58:51.420 --> 01:58:56.540
[Guest 1]: me with this stuff also I wonder to what extent social media has a role to play here right the

01:58:56.540 --> 01:59:02.460
[Guest 1]: kind of economists who are vocal on social media are probably of a very different type believing

01:59:02.460 --> 01:59:07.660
[Guest 1]: in some things as wanting to support the government wanting to come across as I don't want to criticize

01:59:07.660 --> 01:59:11.820
[Guest 1]: the government for anything for whatever reason they may have in their minds and I think that's

01:59:11.820 --> 01:59:16.540
[Guest 1]: what the people who are also on social media get to witness and read and in their mind these are

01:59:16.540 --> 01:59:20.540
[Guest 1]: the economists who have all the power and who have all the prestige and everything and they have

01:59:20.540 --> 01:59:23.820
[Guest 1]: access to the government and they are the ones who are messing up with the economy and they are

01:59:23.820 --> 01:59:27.500
[Guest 1]: the so it's like a you know that is what is getting created using this social media I'm

01:59:27.500 --> 01:59:31.900
[Guest 1]: completely guessing because I myself am not on social media see you're like I could say to you

01:59:31.900 --> 01:59:36.940
[Amit Varma]: what the factory owner said to her that you know yeah yes I don't know the economy because I'm not

01:59:36.940 --> 01:59:41.100
[Amit Varma]: on social media in the sense you don't know social media because you're not on social media

01:59:44.780 --> 01:59:49.420
[Guest 1]: I mean what Shaina would not say in the party that I'm guessing here I am admitting I'm guessing

01:59:49.420 --> 01:59:55.660
[Amit Varma]: that this could be happening in social media my senses and you're right you're right to what I'd

01:59:55.660 --> 02:00:01.420
[Amit Varma]: add to this is that I think social media incentivizes extreme expression because and

02:00:01.420 --> 02:00:06.620
[Amit Varma]: it's almost the opposite of what people call the median voter theorem right the median voter theorem

02:00:06.620 --> 02:00:11.420
[Amit Varma]: basically is that in a democracy with two parties both of them will be as close to the center as

02:00:11.420 --> 02:00:16.060
[Amit Varma]: possible they'll practically be identical in the same way that if you have an ice cream vendor on

02:00:16.060 --> 02:00:20.860
[Amit Varma]: a beach you know he can put his cart anywhere but if there are two of them they'll both try to be as

02:00:20.860 --> 02:00:25.580
[Amit Varma]: close to the center as possible so they have the largest whatever which is why in the US you used

02:00:25.580 --> 02:00:30.060
[Amit Varma]: to have a situation where during the primaries people would swing to the extremes and talk to

02:00:30.060 --> 02:00:35.100
[Amit Varma]: the core voters but during the main elections they'd be next to each other so when I look at

02:00:35.100 --> 02:00:40.060
[Amit Varma]: 2016 for example uh you know two candidates from the different parties who were really close to

02:00:40.060 --> 02:00:45.340
[Amit Varma]: each other in everything were Jeb Bush and Hillary Clinton and of course someone on the extremes won

02:00:45.340 --> 02:00:49.740
[Amit Varma]: and that swing to the extreme so I think what social media also does is once you join social

02:00:49.740 --> 02:00:54.300
[Amit Varma]: media if you get attracted to say an ideological tribe of any kind on either side if you want to

02:00:54.300 --> 02:00:59.500
[Amit Varma]: raise your status within that tribe you know how do you do it by becoming more and more shrill

02:00:59.500 --> 02:01:05.500
[Amit Varma]: and it's a race to the extremes like even that uh Mahasamyalan of so-called Hindu priests which we

02:01:05.500 --> 02:01:11.260
[Amit Varma]: had you know people like Yati Narsinanand and all that you know if any of them was to individually

02:01:11.260 --> 02:01:16.380
[Amit Varma]: give a speech anywhere I don't think they would be so rabid but by the fact that they're all

02:01:16.380 --> 02:01:20.460
[Amit Varma]: together and they all want to stand out and in a sense are competing for the attention

02:01:20.460 --> 02:01:25.740
[Amit Varma]: I think they were driven to even further extremes and then solidified in those positions also I

02:01:25.740 --> 02:01:30.780
[Guest 1]: think I mean what this reflects is the overarching growing trend of polarization in the country

02:01:30.780 --> 02:01:35.980
[Guest 1]: exactly right I mean this is if despite social media being around this was not the case pre-2014

02:01:35.980 --> 02:01:41.420
[Guest 1]: to this extent and the growing trend of polarization has also polarized economists and

02:01:41.420 --> 02:01:45.420
[Guest 1]: economists who are vocal on social media and I and I do read them occasionally when they're writing

02:01:45.420 --> 02:01:52.140
[Guest 1]: their op-eds and giving speeches it's absolutely obnoxious because they know I'm hoping they know

02:01:52.140 --> 02:01:56.700
[Guest 1]: that no economic theory logic argument would support what they're saying but they are saying

02:01:56.700 --> 02:02:00.460
[Guest 1]: what they're saying because they have certain other motives and positions and rank in mind

02:02:00.460 --> 02:02:04.540
[Guest 1]: and that that's the great disservice they are doing to the larger community of economists and

02:02:04.540 --> 02:02:09.260
[Guest 1]: we are all getting confused and conflated together as we all belong to that one entity which is not

02:02:09.260 --> 02:02:13.500
[Amit Varma]: true one minority of spineless people no I remember in fact after demonetization and

02:02:14.060 --> 02:02:18.860
[Amit Varma]: diktat went out to all their you know people under the pay that you got to defend it in public

02:02:18.860 --> 02:02:24.300
[Amit Varma]: so you had people defending demonetization through columns or through tv soundbites in

02:02:24.300 --> 02:02:28.700
[Amit Varma]: ways that you know that this guy has written excellent books this guy is smart he knows this

02:02:28.700 --> 02:02:34.300
[Guest 1]: is not true still he's talking nonsense during demonetization I was extremely vocal on tv

02:02:34.300 --> 02:02:39.580
[Guest 1]: channels I was getting invited by prominent tv channels one of the tv channels itself got

02:02:40.220 --> 02:02:44.300
[Guest 1]: suffered as a result I think so I was getting called in tv channels I was writing in the media

02:02:44.300 --> 02:02:48.780
[Guest 1]: because it was a complete shock to my system the way I know of it forget economics the way I know

02:02:48.780 --> 02:02:53.980
[Guest 1]: the country to be the way I know the people to be the very fact that nobody protested I still can't

02:02:53.980 --> 02:02:59.180
[Guest 1]: fathom that right so I was very vocal about it but then lo and behold after a couple of months I was

02:02:59.180 --> 02:03:05.980
[Guest 1]: indirectly told that I am voicing my opinion too much and it's coming out as too anti-establishment

02:03:05.980 --> 02:03:12.220
[Guest 1]: and I need to tone it down so imagine I mean I am as small and trivial in the larger scheme of things

02:03:12.220 --> 02:03:17.900
[Guest 1]: as can be if I am facing some backlash of this kind what other more prominent people would be

02:03:17.900 --> 02:03:22.460
[Guest 1]: facing if they wanted to speak up against demon and and since then as I said it's been a slippery

02:03:22.460 --> 02:03:26.940
[Guest 1]: slope downhill because you just can't speak up against establishment I mean I did a lot of work

02:03:26.940 --> 02:03:32.060
[Guest 1]: against the GDP data the official GDP data but then there's backlash there as well you just

02:03:32.060 --> 02:03:37.580
[Guest 1]: can't criticize anything that is wrong in the establishment in the polity in the policy in the

02:03:37.580 --> 02:03:43.260
[Guest 1]: economic space and therefore the economists who are getting legitimacy who are getting the sort

02:03:43.260 --> 02:03:48.380
